The '''Gujarati people''' or '''Gujaratis''' ({{lang-gu|ગુજરાતી}}) are an [[ethnic group]] traditionally from [[Gujarat]] that speak [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]], an [[Indo-Aryan languages|Indo-Aryan language]]. Gujaratis are very prominent in industry and key figures played a historic role in the introduction of the doctrine of [[Swaraj]] and the [[Indian independence movement]] in [[British Raj|British-ruled India]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=M. K. Gandhi|title=Hind Swaraj: Indian Home Rule|date=2014|publisher=Sarva Seva Sangh Prakashan|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=29hvBgAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=swaraj,+gujaratis&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj0oMWZ9tPJAhUKnBoKHcjlC4sQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=swaraj%2C%20gujaratis&f=false|accessdate=11 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Minahan|first1=James B.|title=Ethnic groups of South Asia and the Pacific : an encyclopedia|date=2012|publisher=ABC-CLIO|location=Santa Barbara, Calif.|isbn=1598846590|page=90|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=abNDLZQ6quYC&pg=PA90&dq=gujaratis,+indian+independence&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7-vGn0tbJAhVImBoKHfX9DWcQ6AEIKDAA#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20indian%20independence&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2015|quote=Anti-British sentiment led to a strong Gujarati participation in the Indian independence movement.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Yagnik|first1=Achyut|last2=Sheth|first2=Suchitra|title=The shaping of modern Gujarat : plurality, Hindutva, and beyond|date=2005|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi|isbn=0144000385|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wmKIiAPgnF0C&printsec=frontcover&dq=shaping+of+modern+gujarat&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiX77SRpdfJAhXFtBoKHWQ4CzMQ6AEIHzAA#v=onepage&q=shaping%20of%20modern%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2015}}</ref> Gujarati people are descended from [[Aryan]] nomads who rose in the fertile valleys of the [[Indus River]] in 2000 BC and settled in [[Gujarat]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lanuwRB85noC&pg=PA190|title=Great American Hoteliers: Pioneers of the Hotel Industry|first=Stanley|last=Turkel|year=2009|publisher=[[AuthorHouse]]|page=190|ISBN=9781449007522}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=The other Americans: how immigrants renew our country, our economy, and our values|first=Joel|last=Millman|year=1998|ISBN=9780140242171|publisher=[[Penguin Books]]|via=[[Pennsylvania State University]]|page=143}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|title=AAHOA Hospitality|volume=2|author=[[Asian American Hotel Owners Association]]|publisher=Nelson Advantage|page=26|year=1997}}</ref>

==Geographical locations==
Albeit with huge migration for economic reasons, most Gujaratis in India live in the state of [[Gujarat]] in [[Western India]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Singh|first1=A. Didar|last2=Rajan|first2=S. Irudaya|title=Politics of Migration: Indian Emigration in a Globalised World|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317412243|page=141|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VgbgCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA138&dq=GUJARATIS,+ECONOMIC+MIGRATIONS&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=GUJARATIS%2C%20ECONOMIC%20MIGRATIONS&f=false|language=en|quote=Gujarat has a very strong history of migration. The ancient Gujaratis were known for their trading with other countries. The Mercantile caste of western India, including Gujarat, has participated in overseas trade for many centuries and, as new opportunities arose in different parts of the British Empire, they were among the first to emigrate... The Gujarati Diaspora community is well known for their legendary entrepreneurship.}}</ref> Gujaratis also form a significant part of the populations in the neighboring metropolis of [[Mumbai]] and union territories of [[Daman district, India|Daman]] and [[Diu, India|Diu]], and Dadra Nagar Haveli, both being former Portuguese colonies.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Bhargava|first1=ed. S.C. Bhatt, Gopal K.|title=Daman & Diu|date=2006|publisher=Kalpaz publ.|location=Delhi|isbn=81-7835-389-X|page=17|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3IWXh-6zDe8C&pg=PA18&dq=daman+and+diu,+portuguese&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eSbSVO2sJ8bqUo_SgdgB&ved=0CEcQ6AEwBw#v=onepage&q=daman%20and%20diu%2C%20portuguese&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=}}</ref> There are very large Gujarati immigrant communities in other parts of India, most notably in [[Mumbai]],<ref>{{cite book|last1=Blank|first1=Jonah|title=Mullahs on the Mainframe: Islam and Modernity Among the Daudi Bohras|publisher=The University of Chicago Press|isbn=0-226-05677-5|page=47|quote=Modern-day Mumbai is the capital of the state of Maharashtra, but until the creation of this state in 1960 the city has always been as closely linked to Gujarati culture as it has been to Marathi culture. During most of the colonial period, Gujaratis held the preponderance of economic and political power.}}</ref> [[Delhi]], [[Calcutta]], [[Madras]], [[Bangalore]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Raymond Brady Williams|title=A New Face of Hinduism: The Swaminarayan Religion|publisher=Cambridge University Press 1984|isbn=0-521-25454-X|page=117|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AHI7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA170&dq=Oman,+gujaratis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AjjSVIrSGYTxUsT6gKAO&ved=0CFwQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Oman%2C%20gujaratis&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> and other metropolitan areas like [[Kollam]] and [[Kochi]] in [[Kerala]].<ref name="cc">{{cite web | url=http://www.countercurrents.org/shaji230607.htm | title=Rubber Boom Raises Hope Of Repatriates | publisher=Counter Currents | accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/article191293.ece |title=Gujarat should learn from Kerala - The New Indian Express |accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> All throughout history<ref>{{cite book|author1=Edward A. Alpers|title=Ivory and Slaves: Changing Pattern of International Trade in East Central Africa|date=1975|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=0-520-02689-6|page=88|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uKYYwVTyOm0C&pg=PA88&dq=virji+vora&hl=en&sa=X&ei=1zDSVO6hGMr3UIHCgNAF&ved=0CD4Q6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=virji%20vora&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=In the early 1660s, Surat merchants had 50 ships trading overseas, and the wealthiest of these, Virji Vora had an estate valued at perhaps 8 million rupees...}}</ref> Gujaratis have earned a reputation as being India's greatest merchants,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Peck|first1=Amelia|title=Interwoven Globe: The Worldwide Textile Trade, 1500-1800|publisher=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, New York|isbn=978-1-58839-496-5|page=15|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BYjh82N63IQC&pg=PA15&dq=gujarati+merchants,+red+sea&hl=en&sa=X&ei=MyzSVODML4PzUpSSgtAI&ved=0CD4Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20merchants%2C%20red%20sea&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Of the Asian trading communities the most successful were the Gujaratis, as witnessed not only by Pires and Barbosa but by a variety of other sources. All confirm that merchants from the Gujarati community routinely held the most senior post open to an expatriate trader, that of shah-bandar (controller of maritime trade).}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Farhat Hasan|title=State and Locality in Mughal India: Power Relations in Western India, C.1572 - 1730|date=2004|publisher=University Press, Cambridge|isbn=0-521-841 19-4|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4TbxNT70UPEC&pg=PA42&dq=surat+merchants&hl=en&sa=X&ei=32nTVNKbEIP6Up6qhOgL&ved=0CDQQ6AEwBA#v=onepage&q=surat%20merchants&f=false|accessdate=5 February 2015|quote=Mulla Abdul Ghafur, one of the richest merchants in Surat, his son, Mulla Abdul Hai, was awarded the title of 'umdat-tud-tujjar' (lit. the most eminent merchant) by the imperial court. Shantidas Shahu, a powerful merchant of Surat, was gifted an elephant and robe by the emperor, both things being emblems of imperial sovereignty, that 'symbolized the incorporation of the recipient into his [King's] person as his subordinate, to act in future as an extension of himself.}}</ref> industrialists and business [[entrepreneur]]s,<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mehta|first1=Makrand|title=Indian merchants and entrepreneurs in historical perspective : with special reference to shroffs of Gujarat, 17th to 19th centuries|date=1991|publisher=Academic Foundation|location=Delhi|isbn=8171880177|pages=21, 27|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9lz3gNDMbWEC&pg=PA21&dq=gujarati+business,+ancient&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAGoVChMIreS3hp3oyAIViXk-Ch1GbwIR#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20business%2C%20ancient&f=false|accessdate=29 October 2015|quote=The Gujarat region situated in the western part of India is known for its business activities since ancient times. The region has been agriculturally fertile and it also contains a long sea-coast enabling the merchants to undertake overseas trade. Thevenot held the Gujarati merchants in high esteem. Commending them for their skills in the currency business he states that he saw some 15000 banians in Ispahan, the capital of Persia operating exclusively as money-lenders and sharafs. He compared them with the Jews of Turkey and pointed out that they had their own residential settlements at Basra and Ormuz where they had constructed their temples.}}</ref> and have therefore been at forefront of migrations all over the world, particularly to regions that were part of the British empire such as [[Fiji]], [[Hong Kong]], [[New Zealand]], [[East Africa]] and countries in [[Southern Africa]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Kalpana Hiralal|title=Indian Family Businesses in Natal, 1870 – 1950|publisher=Natal Society Foundation 2010|url=http://www.natalia.org.za/Files/38/Natalia%2038%20pp27-37%20C.pdf|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> Diasporas and transnational networks in many of these countries date back to more than a century.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Poros|first1=Maritsa V.|title=Modern Migrations Gujarati Indian Networks in New York and London.|date=2010|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Palo Alto|isbn=0804775834|page=10|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Twg4HqWJ65sC&pg=PA16&lpg=PA16&dq=gujaratis,+transnational+network&source=bl&ots=_D_J5KCxDE&sig=uNtkhmkjylYuIbhtkhLKo4G4Nsg&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20transnational%20network&f=false|quote=However, Gujaratis have been migrating as part of wide-ranging trade diasporas for centuries, long before capitalist development became concentrated in Europe and the United States.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Vinay Lal|title=Diaspora Purana: The Indic Presence in World Culture|url=https://www.sscnet.ucla.edu/southasia/Diaspora/indic_presence.html|accessdate=22 October 2015|quote=Most historians, even those who have sought to move away from the narratives furnished by the framework of colonial knowledge, are unable to begin their narrative of the Indian diaspora before the nineteenth century, but the Gujaratis had justly established a diasporic presence in the early part of the second millennium. So renowned had the Gujaratis become for their entrepreneurial spirit, commercial networks, and business acumen that a bill of credit issued by a Gujarati merchant would be honored as far as 5,000 miles away merely on the strength of the community's business reputation. They traversed the vast spaces of the Indian Ocean world with confidence, and a Gujarati pilot guided Vasco da Gama's ship to India... Under Portuguese rule the Indian Ocean trading system went into precipitous decline, and not until the nineteenth century did the Gujarati diaspora find a new lease of life. Gujarati traders migrated under the British dispensation in large numbers to Kenya, Tanganyika, South Africa, and Fiji, among other places, and Mohandas Gandhi, himself a Gujarati, has recorded that the early political proceedings of the Indian community in South Africa were conducted in the Gujarati language. In East Africa their presence was so prominent that banknotes in Kenya, before the country acquired independence, had inscriptions in Gujarati. Khojas, or Gujarati Ismailis, flourished and even occupied positions as teachers and educators in Muslim countries around the world.}}</ref> In recent decades, larger numbers of Gujaratis have migrated to English speaking countries such as the [[United Kingdom]], [[Australia]], [[Canada]] and the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Seeing Krishna in America The Hindu Bhakti Tradition of Vallabhacharya in India and Its Movement to the West.|date=2014|publisher=McFarland Publishing|isbn=9780786459735|pages=48, 49|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BWQMBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA49&lpg=PA49&dq=gujarati+migration,+america&source=bl&ots=_rowmmo_xi&sig=jpen52g-16EkMYjAn72yZgGIJCk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CGIQ6AEwC2oVChMIhpzJuO7byAIVTL4UCh2EcgiZ#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20migration%2C%20america&f=false|accessdate=24 October 2015|quote=Among Gujaratis, emigration from India has a long history that has also affected Pushtimargiyas. As a seacoast mercantile population, the migration patterns of Gujaratis are ancient and may extend back over two millennia.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Peggy Levitt|title=Towards an Understanding of Transnational Community Forms and Their Impact on Immigrant Incorporation|url=https://migration.ucdavis.edu/rs/more.php?id=47|website=research & seminars|accessdate=25 October 2015|quote=In the Indian case, though organizational arrangements encourage U.S. and sending-country involvements, and the community displays high levels of economic and political integration, the goals of participation in home-country groups, the requirements of membership, and the insular social milieu in which participation occurs, reinforces homeland ties. Gujaratis may become the most transnational of groups because they assimilate selectively into the U.S. and maintain strong sending-country attachments}}</ref>

==History==
Between 1790-1, an epidemic devastated numerous parts of Gujarat during which 100,000 Gujaratis were killed in [[Surat]] alone.<ref>{{cite book|page=193|title=Eighteenth-Century Gujarat: The Dynamics of Its Political Economy, 1750-1800|url=https://books.google.com.sg/books?id=En_heITTXCoC&pg=PA193|author=Ghulam A. Nadri}}</ref>

An outbreak of [[bubonic plague]] in 1812 has been claimed to have killed about half the Gujarati population.<ref name="PetersenChen2017">{{cite book|author1=Eskild Petersen|author2=Lin Hwei Chen|author3=Patricia Schlagenhauf-Lawlor|title=Infectious Diseases: A Geographic Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VPEjDgAAQBAJ&pg=PA8|date=14 February 2017|publisher=Wiley|isbn=978-1-119-08573-7|page=8}}</ref>

[[File:Ludovico-di-Varthema-King-of-Khambat-16th-century-India.jpg|thumb|The king of Cambay (in present-day Gujarat) from “Figurae variae Asiae et Africae," a 16th-century Portuguese manuscript in the Casanatense Library in Rome (Codex Casanatense 1889)]]
Early European travelers like [[Ludovico di Varthema]] (15th century) traveled to Gujarat and wrote on the people of Gujarat. He noted that [[Jainism in Gujarat|Jainism]] had a strong presence in Gujarat and opined that Gujaratis were deprived of their kingdom by Mughals because of their kind heartedness. His description of Gujaratis was:<ref>André Wink (1997) ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=75FlxDhZWpwC&pg=PA434&dq=ISBN+90-04-10236-1&hl=en&ei=1VZyTKOUIpb4vAP2oMFD&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=2&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=heathens&f=false Al-Hind, the Making of the Indo-Islamic World: The Slavic Kings and the Islamic conquest]'', BRILL {{ISBN|90-04-10236-1}} pp.355–356</ref>

{{cquote|...a certain race which eats nothing that has blood, never kills any living things... and these people are neither moors nor heathens... if they were baptized, they would all be saved by the virtue of their works, for they never do to others what they would not do unto them.}}

==Social stratification==
Orthodox Gujarati society which was [[mercantile]] by nature,<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarat & India Same, Different But Same|url=http://www.outlookindia.com/magazine/story/gujarat-india-same-different-but-same/290783|website= outlookindia.com|quote=A historically mercantile culture, widespread influence of Jainism, diluted casteism and an intrinsic irreverence makes society and polity in Gujarat different from other Indian states. Centre-right in their economic leaning, people here naturally gravitate towards leaner governments with high standards of governance... Absence of local rulers’ courts meant that trade-mercantile guilds ran affairs and administration. The kind of socio-cultural influence that pervaded the feudal kingdoms of Rajasthan etc was absent in Gujarat. The trade guilds were akin to the influential mercantile guilds of Belgium and the Netherlands, which contributed to making the Dutch world leaders in finance. In Gujarat, this cascaded into a strong entrepreneurial culture. As the English philosopher Bertrand Russell puts it, governments which consist of mercantilists tend to be more prudent in running the administration.}}</ref> was historically organized along [[ethno-religious]] lines and shaped into existence on the strength of its [[Mahajan]] ("[[guild]] assemblies"),<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jacobsen|first1=Knut A.|title=Routledge Handbook of Contemporary India|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317403586|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=--9WCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA275&dq=mahajan,+gujarati&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=mahajan%2C%20gujarati&f=false|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Pearson|first1=Michael Naylor|title=Merchants and Rulers in Gujarat: The Response to the Portuguese in the Sixteenth Century|publisher=University of California Press|isbn=9780520028098|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yVPn43u846AC&pg=PA124&lpg=PA124&dq=history+of+mahajans+in+gujarat&source=bl&ots=6CStry4fwX&sig=whdJFC4n2l-gjjau-QReANsbCpc&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=history%20of%20mahajans%20in%20gujarat&f=false|language=en|quote=Mahajan means different things in different parts of India; it can refer to an individual banker, a money-lender, a merchant, or an unspecified "great man". In Gujarat it usually meant a body representing a group of people engaged in the same commercial occupation, a governing council with an elected or occasionally hereditary headman...}}</ref> and for its institution of Nagarsheth ("head of the guild assembly"); a 16th-century [[Mughal Empire|Mughal]] system akin to medieval European [[guilds]] which self-regulated the mercantile affairs of multi-ethnic, multi-religious communities in the Gujarati [[bourgeoisie]] long before municipal state politics was introduced.<ref>{{cite web|title=Going global|url=https://www.economist.com/news/christmas-specials/21683983-secrets-worlds-best-businesspeople-going-global|website=The Economist|date=19 December 2015|quote=Whereas one religion, Protestantism, has often been associated with the rise of Anglo-Saxon capitalism, Gujarati capitalism was much more a fusion of influences. Ethnic and religious diversity became a source of strength, multiplying the trading networks that each community could exploit. Pragmatism and flexibility over identity, and a willingness to accommodate, perhaps inherited from the mahajans, are strong Gujarati traits, argues Edward Simpson of the School of Oriental and African Studies at the University of London. Gujaratis have been adept at remaining proudly Gujarati while becoming patriotically British, Ugandan or Fijian—an asset in a globalised economy.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Sundar|first1=Pushpa|title=Business and Community: The Story of Corporate Social Responsibility in India|publisher=SAGE Publications India|isbn=9788132111535|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=seiICwAAQBAJ&pg=PA55&dq=mahajan,+gujarati&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=mahajan%2C%20gujarati&f=false|language=en|quote=The merchants were organized into mahajans or guilds with hereditary seths. A mahajan could include merchants of different religions and there was no strict segregation of religious, social, and occupational functions.}}</ref> Historically, Gujaratis belonging to numerous faiths and [[castes]], thrived in an inclusive climate surcharged by a degree of [[cultural syncretism]], in which Hindus and [[Jains]] dominated occupations such as [[Banker|shroff]]s and brokers whereas, [[Gujarati Muslims|Muslims]], [[Hindu]]s and [[Parsi]]s largely dominated sea shipping trade. This led to religious [[interdependence]], tolerance, [[Cultural assimilation|assimilation]] and [[community cohesion]] ultimately becoming the hallmark of modern-day Gujarati society.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rai|first1=Rajesh|last2=Reeves|first2=Peter|last3=Pro|first3=Visiting Professor Coordinator South Asia Studies Programme Peter Reeves|title=The South Asian Diaspora: Transnational Networks and Changing Identities|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781134105953|page=41|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bwJD2WBNtNMC&pg=PA41&lpg=PA41&dq=gujarat+muslims,+shipping&source=bl&ots=po6sKbSTPM&sig=4Xv7jaiF_ePlOWrDYZZGnK_h94k&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjTo6L4hfnPAhXJDcAKHcwbDg4Q6AEINzAG#v=onepage&q=gujarat%20muslims%2C%20shipping&f=false|language=en|quote=For Banias and Muslims there was a clear division of commercial activities based on religious persuasions and canonical injunctions. For example, Muslim merchants did not deal in printed textiles with motifs of living creatures on it, while these were procured by the Bania and Jain brokers. On the other hand Bania and Jain merchants would not deal in the trade of animals while Muslims did not have any problems with such trade. Similarly, Muslim merchants dominated the shipping trade and many were big ship-owners. The nakhudas and the lascars were also primarily from the Muslim community. On the other hand, some of the Banias and the Jains were prominent merchants and they organized an extensive trade from Gujarat to other parts of Asia. Thus, two forms of trade which formed the shipping and commerce were controlled by these two major communities of Gujarati merchants. For both these communities their relationship necessitated mutual understanding and interdependence in commercial matters so that they could play a complementary role in advancing their trading interests}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Malik|first1=Ashish|last2=Pereira|first2=Vijay|title=Indian Culture and Work Organisations in Transition|publisher=Routledge|isbn=9781317232025|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hCUFDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA190&dq=gujarati,+society&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwis8Yaj4PbPAhWKIMAKHSSNDM84ChDoAQgbMAA#v=onepage&q=gujarati%2C%20society&f=false|language=en|quote=He found that Gujaratis are highly family-oriented valuing family network and highly familial. They are also spiritualistic, religious and relationship oriented, attaching importance to co-operation. They are accepted to be materialistic. Panda, on the basis of empirical evidence, has named the society as 'collectivist familial (clannish) society'. Further, Gujarati society is found to have a high social capital. The dominant cultural characteristics identified from this study, which are essentially 'familial', 'co-operative' and 'non-hierarchical' (democratic) are consistent with Joshi's findings.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Berger|first1=Peter|last2=Heidemann|first2=Frank|title=The Modern Anthropology of India: Ethnography, Themes and Theory|publisher=Routledge|isbn=1134061110|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=sBgLb8XIGR8C&pg=PA84&dq=gujaratis,+uk,+anthropology+of+india&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20uk%2C%20anthropology%20of%20india&f=false|language=en|quote=Gujaratis continuously redefine and contest caste and hiearchical values in a competitive pluralistic social environment. In post-colonial Gujarat, the merchant culture and its values of purity and economic wealth have prevailed over plural notions of hierarchy (Tambs-Lyche 1982)}}</ref>

===Religion===
The Gujarati people are predominantly [[Hindu]]. There are also significant populations of [[Jainism|Jains]] and [[Gujarati Muslims|Muslims]], and minor populations of [[Buddhism|Buddhists]], [[Parsis|Zoroastrians]], [[History of the Jews in India|Jews]] and [[Christianity in India|Christians]]<ref name=religion>{{cite web|title=Gujarat Religion Census 2011|url=http://www.census2011.co.in/data/religion/state/24-gujarat.html|website=Census of India, 2011|publisher=The Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Anjali H. Desai|title=India Guide Gujarat|publisher=India Guide Publications|isbn=9780978951702|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gZRLGZNZEoEC&pg=PA37|language=en}}</ref>

===Hindu Communities===
The major communities in Gujarat are the traditional Agriculturalist such as [[Patel]], [[Ahir]], [[Bharvad]], and [[Rabari]], Artisan communities ([[Gurjar]], [[Prajapati]], [[Bhambi Sindhi Mochi|Sindhi Mochi]]), [[Brahmin]] communities (such as [[Anavil]], [[Nagar Brahmin|Nagar]], [[Modh]]), Farming communities (such as [[Anjana Chaudhari|Choudhary Jats]] and [[Koli people]], Genealogist communities (such as [[Charans]] and [[Barot (caste)|Barot]]s), [[Kshatriya]] communities (such as [[Koli people|Koli]] [[Thakor]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books?id=IWrTs5yt1DkC&pg=PA1363&dq=Thakore&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjO5bq8mcHeAhVJb30KHS3DA8EQ6AEILDAD#v=onepage&q=Thakore&f=false|title=Gujarat|date=2003|publisher=Popular Prakashan|isbn=9788179911068|language=en}}</ref>, [[Bhanushali|Banushali]], [[Kathi Darbar]]s, [[Karadiya Rajput|Karadia]], [[Chudasama]], [[Mahar (tribe)|Maher]]), Parsi Community, Tribal communities (such as [[Bhils]], [[Meghwal]] and [[Kolis]]) and [[Vaishya]] (such as [[Bhatia caste|Bhatia]], [[Lohana]], [[Soni (caste)|Soni]]).

===Muslim Communities===
The major Gujarati Muslim communities include [[Bhadala]], [[Daudi Bohra]], [[memon people|Memon]], [[Khoja]], [[Sayyid of Gujarat|Sayyid]], [[Siddhi]] and Vahora.

==Diaspora==
Gujaratis have a long tradition of seafaring and a history of overseas migration to foreign lands, to [[Yemen]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Pedro Machado|title=Ocean of Trade: South Asian merchants, Africa and the Indian Ocean, c.1750 - 1850|date=2014|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-1-107-07026-4|page=20|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ODfJBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA20&dq=gujaratis,+kuwait&hl=en&sa=X&ei=JDrSVN-8EIqtUeGrhJAI&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20kuwait&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Hindu Vaniya networks from Kathiawar, in particular, operated prominently in the region, and directed their trade primarily to Yemen, and Hadramawt. They were also active in the early eighteenth century in the southern Red Sea, where Mocha and other ports such as Aden provided them with their principal markets}}</ref> [[Oman]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Cordell Crownover|title=Ultimate Handbook Guide to Muscat : (Oman) Travel Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BRDGBAAAQBAJ&pg=PP6&dq=Oman,+gujaratis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=AjjSVIrSGYTxUsT6gKAO&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=Oman%2C%20gujaratis&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=As an important port-town in the Gulf of Oman, Muscat attracted foreign tradesman and settlers, such as the Persians, the Balochs and Gujaratis.}}</ref> [[Bahrain]],<ref>{{cite book|author1=Andrew Gardner|title=City of Strangers: Gulf Migration and the Indian Community in Bahrain|date=1969|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-7602-0|page=77|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5QTI_GG8cB0C&pg=PA77&dq=gujaratis,+in+bahrain&hl=en&sa=X&ei=rHTSVMKeEoT_Up-jhOgI&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAQ#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20in%20bahrain&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Other Indian groups with a long-standing presence in Bahrain include the Gujarati businessmen whose enterprises historically centered on the trade of gold; the Bohra community, an Indian Muslim sect with a belief system particularly configured around business...}}</ref> Kuwait, [[Zanzibar]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ababu Minda Yimene|title=An African Indian Community in Hyderabad: Siddi Identity, Its Maintenance and Change|date=2004|isbn=3-86537-206-6|pages=66, 67|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DigPvwHTqJ4C&pg=PA67&dq=gujaratis+in+england,+19th+century&hl=en&sa=X&ei=eEXSVPPCNofrUrLsgMAG&ved=0CE0Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%20in%20england%2C%2019th%20century&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Some centuries later, the Gujarati merchants established permanent trading posts in Zanzibar, consolidating their influence in the Indian Ocean... Gujarati Muslims, and their Omani partners, engaged in a network of mercantile activities among Oman, Zanzibar and Bombay. Thanks to those mercantile Gujarati, India remained by far the principal trading partner of Zanzibar.}}</ref> and other countries in the [[Persian Gulf]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Irfan Habib|title=Economic History of Medieval India, 1200-1500|isbn=978-81-317-2791-1|page=166|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K8kO4J3mXUAC&pg=PA166&dq=gujarati+merchants,+Iran&hl=en&sa=X&ei=pTzSVMzZHMv4UMaTg5AE&ved=0CFcQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20merchants%2C%20Iran&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=In the Persian Gulf, Hurmuz (Hormuz), was the most important entrepot for the international exchange for goods which were either bartered or purchased with money. The rise of Hurmuz in the thirteenth century followed the decline of the neighbouring entrepot of Qays, where there was a community of Gujarati Bohra merchants}}</ref> since a mercantile culture resulted naturally from the state's proximity to the Arabian Sea.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Paul R. Magocsi|title=Encyclopedia of Canada's Peoples|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=0-8020-2938-8|page=631|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dbUuX0mnvQMC&pg=PA631&dq=mercantile,+gujaratis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=zzXSVN2yLcixUbfTg8gJ&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=mercantile%2C%20gujaratis&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015|quote=Gujarat's proximity to the Arabian Sea has been responsible for the ceaseless mercantile and maritime activities of its people. Through the ports of Gujarat, some of which date back to the dawn of history, trade and commerce flourished, and colonizers left for distant lands.}}</ref> The countries with the largest Gujarati populations are Pakistan, United Kingdom, United States, Canada and many countries in Southern and East Africa. Globally, Gujaratis are estimated to comprise around 33% of the Indian diaspora worldwide and can be found in 129 of 190 countries listed as sovereign nations by the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Chidanand Rajghatta|title=Global Gujaratis: Now in 129 nations|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2015-01-04/news/57663531_1_gujaratis-patels-united-nations|website=The economic times|accessdate=21 October 2015|quote=A lot of the spread worldwide took place after a pit-stop in East Africa, right across the sea from Gujarat. When Idi Amin turfed out some 100,000 Indians (mostly Gujaratis) from Uganda in 1972, most of them descended on Britain before peeling off elsewhere.}}</ref> [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non Resident Gujaratis]] (NRGs) maintain active links with the homeland in the form of business, [[remittances|remittance]], [[philanthropy]], and through their political contribution to state governed domestic affairs.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Premal Balan & Kalpesh Damor|title=Thanks to NRIs, 3 small Gujarat villages each have Rs 2,000cr bank deposits|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Thanks-to-NRIs-3-small-Gujarat-villages-each-have-Rs-2000cr-bank-deposits/articleshow/47698445.cms|website=the times of india|accessdate=26 October 2015|quote=No wonder bank hoardings flashing interest rates for NRI deposits (up to 10%) is a common sight in these villages. "Some villages in Kutch like Madhapar and Baladia have very high NRI deposits. To the best of our knowledge, this is the highest in the country," said K C Chippa, former convener of the State Level Banker's Committee (SLBC) Gujarat. Between them, Madhapar, Baladia and Kera have 30 bank branches and 24 ATMs.}}</ref><ref name=piyush>{{cite web|author1=Piyush Mishra|title=NRI deposits in Gujarat cross Rs 50K crore mark|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/NRI-deposits-in-Gujarat-cross-Rs-50K-crore-mark/articleshow/47889249.cms|website=the times of India|accessdate=26 October 2015|quote=Gujaratis form 33% of the Indian diaspora and Gujarat is among the top five states in the country in terms of NRI deposits. RBI data shows there was a little over $115 billion (about Rs 7 lakh crore) in NRI accounts in India in 2014-15, with Gujarat accounting for 7.78% of the kitty.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Fernandez-Kelly|editor1-first=Patricia|editor2-last=Portes|editor2-first=Alejandro|title=The State and the Grassroots: Immigrant Transnational Organizations in Four Continents|publisher=Berghahn Books|isbn=9781782387350|page=99|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zyjfCQAAQBAJ&pg=PA99&dq=gujaratis,+NRGs,+politics&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20NRGs%2C%20politics&f=false|accessdate=26 October 2015}}</ref>

Gujarati parents in the diaspora are not comfortable with the possibility of their language not surviving them.<ref name=lang>{{cite book|title=Language in South Asia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=O2n4sFGDEMYC&pg=PA531|page=531|first1=Braj B.|last1=Kachru|first2=Yamuna|last2=Kachru|first3=S. N.|last3=Sridhar|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2008|ISBN=9781139465502}}</ref> In a study, 80% of [[Malayali]] parents felt that "children would be better off with English", compared to 36% of [[Kannada people|Kannada]] parents and only 19% of Gujarati parents.<ref name=lang/>

===Pakistan===
[[File:Photograph of Jinnah with Gandhi in 1944 (Photo 429-17).jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|right|Jinnah with [[Mahatma Gandhi]] in Bombay, 1944]]
{{Main|Demographics of Pakistan}}
There is a community of [[Gujarati Muslims]] mainly settled in the Pakistani [[Administrative units of Pakistan|province]] of [[Sindh]] for generations. Community leaders say there are 3,000,000 speakers of Gujarati language in [[Karachi]].<ref name=pk/> A sizable number migrated after the [[Partition of India]] and subsequent [[Pakistan movement|creation of independent Pakistan]] in 1947. These Pakistani Gujaratis belong mainly to the [[Ismailism|Ismāʿīlī]], [[Khoja]], [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Chundrigar]], [[Sunni Bohra|Charotar Sunni Vohra]], [[Ghanchi (Muslim)|Muslim Ghanchi]], Muslim Khatri and Memon groups; however, many Gujaratis are also a part of Pakistan's small but vibrant [[Hinduism in Pakistan|Hindu community]].<ref>[http://www.thenews.com.pk/print1.asp?id=161405 The Gujaratis of Pakistan] {{dead link|date=June 2016|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> Famous Gujaratis of Pakistan include [[Muhammed Ali Jinnah]] (father of Pakistan), [[Ibrahim Ismail Chundrigar]] (sixth Prime Minister of Pakistan), Sir [[Adamjee Haji Dawood]] (philanthropist), [[Abu Bakr Osman Mitha]] (Major-General), [[Abdul Razzak Yaqoob]] (philanthropist), [[Javed Miandad]] (Pakistani cricketer),<ref>{{cite web|title=JAVED MIANDAD: profile|url=http://www.karismatickarachi.com/karachiites-jm.php|website=karismatickarachi|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> [[Abdul Sattar Edhi]] (humanitarian), [[Jehangir H. Kothari]] (philanthropist),<ref>{{cite web |title = Chapter 9 - Charity Galore in ''Journal of Informal Religious Meetings'', vol. 5(8), Oct/Nov 2004| url= http://www.zoroastrian.org.uk/vohuman/ushao/us73_08.htm}}</ref> [[Abdul Gaffar Billoo]] (philanthropist), [[Sarfraz Ahmed]](Pakistani cricketer), [[Ramzan Chhipa]] (philanthropist), [[Tapu Javeri]] (Pakistani fashion and art photographer), [[Pervez Hoodbhoy]] (Pakistani nuclear physicist)<ref>{{cite web|author1=Khaled Ahmed|title=Gujarat's gifts to India and Pakistan|url=http://tribune.com.pk/story/340710/gujarats-gifts-to-india-and-pakistan/|website=The Express Tribune|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=February 23, 2012}}</ref> and [[Ardeshir Cowasjee]] (Pakistani critic and social activist).<ref>{{cite web|title=The Gujaratis of Pakistan – By Aakar Patel|url=https://lubpak.com/archives/899|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref>

===United States===
[[File:India Square JC jeh.JPG|thumb|Gujaratis have achieved a high [[demographic profile]] in many urban districts worldwide, notably in [[India Square]] in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]], in the [[New York City Metropolitan Area]], United States, as large-scale immigration from India continues into [[New York City|New York]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/yearbook-immigration-statistics-2013-lawful-permanent-residents|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2013 Supplemental Table 2|publisher=U.S. Department of Homeland Security|accessdate=2014-06-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/yearbook-immigration-statistics-2012-legal-permanent-residents|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2012 Supplemental Table 2|publisher=U.S. Department of Homeland Security|accessdate=2013-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/files/statistics/publications/LPR11.shtm|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2011 Supplemental Table 2|publisher=U.S. Department of Homeland Security|accessdate=2013-07-05}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.dhs.gov/files/statistics/publications/LPR10.shtm|title=Yearbook of Immigration Statistics: 2010 Supplemental Table 2|publisher=U.S. Department of Homeland Security|accessdate=2013-07-05}}</ref> with the largest metropolitan Gujarati population outside of India.]]
The United States has the second-largest Gujarati population after Pakistan. The highest concentration of the population of over 100,000 is in the [[New York City Metropolitan Area]] alone, notably in the growing Gujarati diasporic center of [[India Square]] in [[Jersey City, New Jersey|Jersey City]], [[New Jersey]], and [[Edison Township, New Jersey|Edison]] in [[Middlesex County, New Jersey|Middlesex County]] in [[Central New Jersey]]. Significant immigration from India to the United States started after the landmark [[Immigration and Nationality Act of 1965]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Keely|first1=Charles B.|title=Effects of the immigration act of 1965 on selected population characteristics of immigrants to the United States|journal=Demography|date=May 1971|volume= 8|issue=2|pages=157–169|doi=10.2307/2060606}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Khandelwal|first1=MS|title=The politics of space in South asian Diaspora, Chapter 7 Indian immigrants in Queens, New York City: patterns of spatial concentration and distribution, 1965–1990 - Nation and migration: - books.google.com|date=1995|publisher=University of Pennsylvania|location=Philadelphia, USA|isbn=0-8122-3259-3|page=179|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=bvTHlLRZL8UC&oi=fnd&pg=PA178&dq=+Immigration+and+Nationality+Act+of+1965+india+united+states+gujarat&ots=1Mj5geYCgf&sig=Ji9XRIHs0NwSVcwjDwLdDAb5XiU#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=20 June 2015}}</ref> Early immigrants after 1965 were highly educated professionals. Since US immigration laws allow sponsoring immigration of parents, children and particularly siblings on the basis of family reunion, the numbers rapidly swelled in a phenomenon known as "[[chain migration]]".A number of Gujarati are twice or thrice-migrant because they came directly from the former British colonies of East Africa or from East Africa via Great Britain respectively<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rangaswamy|first1=Padma|title=Indian Americans|date=2007|publisher=Chelsea House|location=New York|isbn=9780791087862|page=55|edition=2007 Hardcover Edition.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=kDLYC_XHZuoC&oi=fnd&pg=PA5&dq=jabalpur+navaratri&ots=MJ7F2tBa2e&sig=N3rLotRMKQi6-WZvgCO8D7huLKw#v=onepage&q=gujarati&f=false}}</ref> Given the Gujarati propensity for business enterprise, a number of them opened shops and motels. Now in the 21st century over 40% of the [[hospitality industry]] in the United States is controlled by Gujaratis.<ref>{{cite book|last1=edited by Greve|first1=Joel A.C.|last2=Baum|first2=Henrich R.|last3=Authored by Kalnins|first3=Arthur|last4=Chung|first4=Wilbur|title=Multiunit organization and multimarket strategy|date=2001|publisher=JAI|location=New York|isbn=0-7623-0721-8|pages=33–48|edition=1.|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=23bcHnkX3bUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA31&dq=patel+motel&ots=9KUcTOo9vF&sig=hzqXSQE1sNeFtA0C--8acsBB-jk#v=onepage&q=patel&f=false}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Virani|first1=Aarti|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/indiarealtime/2012/06/11/why-indian-americans-dominate-the-u-s-motel-industry/|title=Why Indian Americans Dominate the U.S. Motel Industry|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=HIRAL DHOLAKIA-DAVE|title=42% of US hotel business is Gujarati|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/world/us/42-of-US-hotel-business-is-Gujarati/articleshow/2191584.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=Oct 18, 2006|quote=Gujaratis, mainly Patels, now own 21,000 of the 53,000 hotels and motels in the US. It makes for a staggering 42% of the US hospitality market, with a combined worth of $40 billion.}}</ref> Gujaratis, especially the Patidar samaj, also dominate as franchisees of fast food restaurant chains such as [[Subway (restaurant)|Subway]] and [[Dunkin' Donuts]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Rangaswami|first1=Padma|title=Namaste America: Indian Immigrants in an American Metropolis|date=2000|publisher=Pennsylvania State University press|location=University park, PA, USA|isbn=0271--01980-8|page=285}}</ref> The descendants of the Gujarati immigrant generation have also made high levels of advancement into [[professional]] fields, including as [[physician]]s, [[engineer]]s and politicians. In August 2016, [[Air India]] commenced single aircraft (no transfer) flight service between [[Ahmedabad]] and [[Newark Liberty International Airport]] in New Jersey, via [[London Heathrow International Airport]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/business/india-business/Air-India-launches-Ahmedabad-to-Newark-flight/articleshow/53710651.cms|title=Air India launches Ahmedabad to Newark flight|author=Ashish Chauhan|newspaper=The Times of India|date=August 15, 2016|accessdate=September 8, 2016}}</ref>

Notable Gujarati Americans include [[Ami Bera]] (United States Congress),<ref>{{cite news|author=Drew Joseph |url=http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?f=/c/a/2010/08/13/BABP1ELANQ.DTL|title=Bera Hopes to Wipe Out Lungren Despite GOP Wave|newspaper=San Francisco Chronicle|date=2010-08-14|accessdate=2010-09-22}}</ref> [[Reshma Saujani]] (American politician),<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Gujarati-woman-aims-for-House-history-in-US/articleshow/5511099.cms "Gujarati Woman Aims for House"], ''The Times of India'', January 1, 2010.</ref> [[Sonal Shah (economist)|Sonal Shah]] (economist to Whitehouse),<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarati NRI Sonal Shah appointed Obama's adviser|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2008/11/06/gujarati-nri-sonal-shah-appointed-obamas-adviser/|website=DeshGujarat|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=NRI Gujarati Sonal Shah, an eminent economist who heads Google's philanthropic arm, has been appointed an advisory board member by US President-elect Barack Obama to assist his team in smooth transition of power.}}</ref> [[Raj Shah]] ([[White House Office of the Press Secretary|White House Deputy Press Secretary]] under President Trump),<ref name="deplorable">{{Cite web |url=http://nymag.com/daily/intelligencer/2018/02/white-house-official-called-trump-a-deplorable.html |title=White House Official Called Trump ‘a Deplorable’ |date=February 5, 2018 |work=[[New York (magazine)|New York]] |last=Nuzzi |first=Olivia}}</ref> [[Rohit Vyas]] (Indian American journalist), 
[[Bharat Desai]] (CEO [[Syntel]]),<ref>{{cite web|title=2 Gujarati-origin among America's super-rich|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/india/report-2-gujarati-origin-among-america-s-super-rich-1442367|website=dna india|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> [[Vyomesh Joshi]] (Forbes),<ref>{{cite web|author1=Raheel Dhattiwala|title=The million dollar man from Gujarat|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2005-08-01/news/27493830_1_manoj-joshi-mark-hurd-b-school|website=The Economic Times|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=AT was lucky to meet the Ahmedabad-born, 50-year-old business honcho in person.}}</ref> [[Romesh Wadhwani]] (Forbes),<ref>{{cite web|title=FIVE INDIAN AMERICANS AMONG FORBES 400 RICHEST|url=http://www.globalgujaratnews.in/print/five-indian-americans-among-forbes-400-richest/|website=global gujarat news|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Next comes Romesh T. Wadhwani (No. 250), Founder and Chairman, Symphony Technology Group, with a net worth of $1.9 billion. Landing in the US with only a few dollars in his pocket, he developed business software firm Aspect Development. Today his portfolio includes more than 10 different enterprise software companies.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Top 10 Richest Gujarati in the India|url=http://www.coolgujarati.com/2018/02/top-10-richest-gujarati-in-india.html|website=global gujarat news|accessdate=23 February 2018|quote=Romesh Wadhwani is the chairman and CEO of Symphony Technology Group, which brings in $2.5 billion in annual revenues. In January 2017 the firm sold MSC Software to Swedish company Hexagon for $834 million. After graduating from the Indian Institute of Technology, he went to Carnegie Mellon and received a Ph.D. in 1972 in electrical engineering.}}</ref> [[Raj Bhavsar]] (sports)<ref>{{cite web|title=IG Online Interview: Raj Bhavsar (USA)|url=http://www.intlgymnast.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=784:interview-raj-bhavsar-usa&catid=3:interviews&Itemid=56|website=intlgymnast|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Born in Houston, Bhavsar is 100 percent Gujarati; his father hails from Vadadora (Baroda), a city in the small Indian state of Gujarat, near Mumbai. His mother was born in Kampala, Uganda, but was educated in Gujurat. Most of Bhavsar's relatives are Gujarati.}}</ref> [[Halim Dhanidia|Halim Dhanidina]] (first Muslim judge of California), [[Savan Kotecha]] ([[Grammy]] nominated American songwriter),<ref>{{cite web|title=Savan Kotecha, Songwriter|url=http://ofindianorigin.co.uk/interview/savan-kotecha-songwriter/|website=ofindianorigin.co.uk|accessdate=24 October 2015|quote=I come from a pretty traditional Gujarati family and that made getting into the music business pretty tricky. My parents like most Indian parents, wanted me to go to Uni and be a Doctor or Lawyer. That meant I was on my own for the most part as far as figuring out how to 'make it'. It also gave me something to prove which made me work extra hard.|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101103010655/http://ofindianorigin.co.uk/interview/savan-kotecha-songwriter/|archive-date=3 November 2010|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and [[Hollywood]] actresses, [[Sheetal Sheth]]<ref>{{cite web|title=Movers and shakers|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/Movers+and+shakers/1/5762.html|website=india today|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote="We are close to our extended families in Ahmedabad and Mumbai and grew up with Gujarati culture as a predominant influence in our lives.... The Gujarati community has done it all in the US — from doctors to entrepreneurs, from retail to the hospitality industry.}}</ref> and [[Noureen DeWulf]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Stereotypes are very hard to escape: Noureen DeWulf|url=http://zeenews.india.com/entertainment/celebrity/stereotypes-are-very-hard-to-escape-noureen-dewulf_61087.html|website=Zee News India|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=DeWulf, a Gujarati Muslim by origin, has carved out a successful career for herself in Hollywood and her repertoire includes Hollywood films like `West Bank Story` and `Ghosts of Girlfriends Past` besides TV shows `Maneater`, `90210` and `Girlfriends`.}}</ref>

===Europe===
====United Kingdom====
[[File:Neasden Temple - Shree Swaminarayan Hindu Mandir - Power Plant.jpg|thumb|upright=1.35|right|The [[Neasden Temple|Swaminarayan Temple]] at Neasden, London which is the largest Hindu Temple in Europe]]

Gujaratis have had a long involvement with Britain. The original [[East India Company]] set up a [[factory (trading post)]] in the port city of [[Surat]] in Gujarat in 1615. These were the beginnings of first real British involvement with India that eventually led to the formation of the [[British Raj]].
The third largest overseas diaspora of Gujaratis, after [[Pakistan]] and United States, is in the UK. At a population of around 600,000<ref name="ukncgo.org">{{cite web|title=Gujaratis in Britain: Profile of a Dynamic Community|url=http://ukncgo.org/gujaratis_britain.html|website=NATIONAL CONGRESS OF GUJARATI ORGANISATIONS (UK)|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> Gujaratis form almost half of the Indian community who live in the UK (1.2 million). Gujaratis first went to the UK in the 19th century with the establishment of the [[British Raj]] in India. Prominent members of this community such as [[Shyamji Krishna Varma]] played a vital role in exerting political pressure upon colonial powers during the [[Indian independence movement]].

The present day Gujarati diaspora in the UK is mostly the second and third generation descendants of "twice-over" immigrants from the former British colonies of East Africa, [[Portugal]], and [[Indian Ocean Islands]]. Most of them despite being [[British Subject]]s had restricted access to Britain after successive Immigration acts of [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1962|1962]], [[Commonwealth Immigrants Act 1968|1968]] and [[Immigration Act 1971|1971]]. Most were, however, eventually admitted on the basis of a Quota voucher system or, in case of Uganda, as refugees after the expulsion order by the [[Uganda]]n ruler, [[Idi Amin]] in [[August 1972]].

Gujaratis in Britain are regarded as affluent middle-class peoples who have assimilated into the milieu of British society.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Derek Laud|title=The Problem With Immigrants|date=2015|publisher=Biteback Publishing|isbn=1849548773|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=GR8mBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT104&lpg=PT104&dq=Gulu+Lalvani,+gujarati&source=bl&ots=zBtWx6qaM7&sig=McgoTjF0YYkrBpYCyOioDMgWN4A&hl=en&sa=X&ei=qYz4VOyTMsHtUr_Tg9gO&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=Gulu%20Lalvani%2C%20gujarati&f=false|accessdate=5 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Shastri Ramachandaran|title=India has much to learn from Britain and Germany|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/analysis/column-india-has-much-to-learn-from-britain-and-germany-2001769|website=dnaindia.com|accessdate=22 October 2015|quote=Britain places high value on the power of commerce. After all, its political and military dominance when Britannia ruled the waves was founded on its trading power. The Gujaratis know this better than many others, which explains their prosperity and success in the UK.}}</ref> They are celebrated for revolutionizing the corner shop, and energising the British economy which changed Britain's antiquated retail laws forever.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-93329/Asian-corner-shops-decline.html#ixzz2e4Fvolgs | location=London | work=Daily Mail | title=Asian corner shops are in decline}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Chitra Unnithan|title=Family is key to success of Gujarati businessmen in Britain|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Family-is-key-to-success-of-Gujarati-businessmen-in-Britain/articleshow/13401987.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=4 February 2015|date=May 23, 2012|quote=British Gujaratis were also more successful than other minority communities in Britain because they had already tasted success in Africa. The book also says that Gujarati Hindus have become notably successful public citizens of contemporary, capitalistic Britain; on the other hand, they maintain close family links with India. "British Gujaratis have been successful in a great variety of fields. Many younger Gujaratis took to professions rather than stay behind the counter of their parents' corner shops, or they entered public life, while those who went into business have not remained in some narrow commercial niche," says the book.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Sudeshna Sen|title=How Gujaratis changed corner shop biz in UK|url=http://blogs.economictimes.indiatimes.com/LettersfromLondon/how-gujaratis-changed-corner-shop-biz-in-uk/|website=The Economic Times|accessdate=4 February 2015|date=January 8, 2013|quote="What most people don't get is that those who took the Arab dhows in the 17th and 18th century to leave their villages and set up life in an alien land were already an entrepreneurial and driven minority, in search of a better life. They communicated that hunger to their children," says Raxa Mehta, director at Nomura, based in Tokyo and first generation child of Kenyan Indian parents. So it doesn't surprise the Gujaratis that they did well in Britain – it only surprises the Brits and Indians. The Gujaratis are a trader community. As Manubhai says, they always left the fighting to the others. If there's one diaspora community that East African Asians model themselves on, it's the Jews. Except of course, the Jews get more publicity than they do.}}</ref> Demographically, Hindus form a majority along with a significant number of [[Jain]]s and Muslims,<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Rodger|first1=R|last2=Herbert|first2=J|title='Narratives of South Asian women in Leicester 1964 - 2004', no. 2, pp..|journal=Oral History|date=2008|volume=36|issue=2|pages=554–563|url=http://www.research.ed.ac.uk/portal/files/15509392/RODGER_Narratives_of_South_Asian_Muslim_Women_in_Leicester_1964_2004.pdf}}</ref> and smaller numbers of [[Christianity in Gujarat|Gujarati Christians]].<ref>{{cite web|title=London's Gujarati Christians celebrate milestone birthday|url=http://www.eauk.org/current-affairs/media/press-releases/londons-gujarati-christians-celebrate-milestone-birthday.cfm|website=www.eauk.org}}</ref> They are predominantly settled in metropolitan areas like [[Greater London]], East Midlands, West Midlands, Lancashire and [[Yorkshire]].<ref name="ukncgo.org"/> Cities with significant Gujarati populations include [[Leicester]] and London boroughs of [[London Borough of Brent|Brent]], [[London Borough of Barnet|Barnet]], [[London Borough of Harrow|Harrow]] and [[London Borough of Wembley|Wembley]]. There is also a small, but vibrant Gujarati-speaking Parsi community of [[Zoroastrians]] present in the country, dating back to the bygone era of [[Dadabhai Navroji]], [[Shapurji Saklatvala]] and [[Pherozeshah Mehta]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Malik|first1=edited by K.N.|last2=Robb|first2=Peter|title=India and Britain : recent past and present challenges|date=1994|publisher=Allied Publishers|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788170233503|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r1tuAAAAMAAJ&q=gujarati,+upper+class,+britain&dq=gujarati,+upper+class,+britain&hl=en&sa=X&ei=_tXTVPzcFIrqUu6egYgO&ved=0CEAQ6AEwBjgK|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref> Both Hindus and Muslims have established caste or community associations, temples, and mosques to cater for the needs of their respective communities. A well known temple popular with Gujaratis is the BAPS [[Neasden Temple|Swaminarayan Temple]] in Neasdon, London. A popular mosque that caters for the Gujarati Muslim community in Leicester is the [[Masjid Umar, Leicester|Masjid Umar]]. Leicester has a Jain Temple that is also the headquarters of Jain Samaj Europe.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jain Samaj Europe |url=http://www.jaincentreleicester.com/our-history.asp |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150123211249/http://www.jaincentreleicester.com/our-history.asp |archivedate=23 January 2015 |df=dmy }}</ref> The [[SPA London|Shree Prajapati Association]] is a charity, already thriving in East Africa, which has 13 branches in the U.K. and is strongly dependent on support from the Gujarati community in Britain.

[[File:Priti Patel 2016.jpg|thumb|upright=0.9|right|[[Priti Patel]] (MP) of UK [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]]]]
Gujarati Hindus in the UK have maintained many traditions from their homeland. The community remains religious with more than 100 temples catering for their religious needs. All major Hindu festivals such as [[Navratri]], Dassara, and [[Diwali]] are celebrated with a lot of enthusiasm even from the generations brought up in UK. Gujarati Hindus also maintain their caste affiliation to some extent with most major castes having their own community association in each population center with significant Gujarati population such as Leicester and London suburbs. [[Patel|Patidars]] form the largest community in the diaspora including Kutch Leva Patels,<ref>{{cite web|title=Shree Kutch Leva Patel Community (UK)|url=http://www.sklpc.com/|website=sklpc.com/}}</ref> followed closely by [[Lohanas]] of [[Saurashtra people|Saurashtra]] origin.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Eliezer Ben Rafael, Yitzhak Sternberg|title=Transnationalism: Diasporas and the Advent of a New (Dis)order|isbn=978-90-04-17470-2|page=531|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QmpgywaZrrgC&pg=PA531&dq=gujarati+patidars,+lohanas,+UK&hl=en&sa=X&ei=kkbSVK2NAYawUZ-NgugO&ved=0CEAQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20patidars%2C%20lohanas%2C%20UK&f=false|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> Gujarati [[Rajputs]] from various regional backgrounds are affiliated with several independent British organizations dependant on caste such as Shree Maher Samaj UK,<ref>{{cite web|title=Shree Maher Samaj UK|url=http://www.maheronline.org/centres/shree-maher-samaj-uk|website=maheronline.org/|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> and the Gujarati Arya Kshatriya Mahasabha-UK.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarati Arya Kshatriya Mahasabha-UK|url=http://www.gakm.co.uk/?p=about|website=gakm.co.uk/?p=about|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref>

Endogamy remains important to Gujarati Muslims in UK with the existence of matrimonial services specifically dedicated to their community.<ref>[http://www.gujaratimuslimmarriage.com Gujarati Muslim Marriage], a dedicated service to assist Gujarati Muslims to marry within the community.</ref> Gujarati Muslim society in the UK have kept the custom of '''Jamat Bandi''', literally meaning communal solidarity. This system is the traditional expression of communal solidarity. It is designed to regulate the affairs of the community and apply sanctions against infractions of the communal code. Gujarati Muslim communities, such as the [[Ismāʿīlī]], Khoja, [[Dawoodi Bohra]], [[Sunni Bohra]], and Memon have [[caste]] associations, known as jamats that run mosques and community centers for their respective communities.

India becoming the predominant [[IT]] powerhouse in the 1990s has led to waves of new immigration by Gujaratis, and other Indians with software skills to the UK.{{Citation needed|date=August 2017}}

====Belgium====
Two Gujarati business communities, the [[Palanpur]]i Jains and the Kathiawadi Patels from Surat, have come to dominate the diamond industry of [[Belgium]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Backman|first1=M|last2=Butler C|first2=C|title=BIG in Asia - Understanding Asia’s Overseas Indians|date=2003|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|location=London|isbn=978-0-230-00027-8|url=https://doi.org/10.1057/9781403914484_4}}</ref> They have largely displaced the [[Orthodox Judaism|Orthodox Jewish]] community which previously dominated this industry in Belgium.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://theconversation.com/the-rise-and-rise-of-belgiums-indian-diamond-dynasties-32332|title=The rise and rise of Belgium’s Indian diamond dynasties|date=October 16, 2014|first=Kathryn|last=Lum|publisher=[[The Conversation (website)|The Conversation]]}}</ref>

===Canada===
Canada, just like its southern neighbour, is home to a large Gujarati community. According to the 2011 National Household Survey, there are 118,950 Gujaratis of various religious backgrounds living in Canada.<ref name="NHS Profile">{{cite web|title=NHS Profile, Canada, 2011, Census Data|url=https://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=Non-official%20language&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1|website=Government of Canada, Statistics Canada|accessdate=4 February 2015}}</ref> The majority of them live in [[Greater Toronto Area|Toronto and its suburbs]] - home to the second largest Gujarati community in North America after the New York Metropolitan Area. Gujarati Hindus are the second largest linguistic/religious group in Canada's Indian community after [[Punjabi people|Punjabi Sikhs]], and Toronto is home to the largest Navratri [[Dandiya Raas|raas garba]] festival in North America.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.torontogarba.com/|title=Toronto Garba: North America's Largest Raas-Garba|website=www.torontogarba.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> The Ismaili Khoja form a significant part of the Canadian diaspora estimated to be about 80,000 in numbers overall.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Al Noor Kassum|title=Africa's winds of change : memoirs of an international Tanzanian|date=2007|publisher=I.B. Tauris|location=London|isbn=978-1-84511-583-8|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=p2H121rsH7cC&pg=PA69&dq=ismaili+population+of+canada&hl=en&sa=X&ei=Z97UVIrGNcyrU5zhgNgD&ved=0CDYQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=ismaili%20population%20of%20canada&f=false|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Most of them arrived in Canada in the 1970s as immigrants from [[Uganda]] and other countries of East Africa.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Versi|first1=Salima|title=Make This Your Home: The Impact of Religion on Acculturation: The Case of Canadian Khoja Nizari Isma'ilis from East Africa|url=http://qspace.library.queensu.ca/handle/1974/5967|publisher=Queens University|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Ajit Jain|title='Gujarati diaspora integral to state's success'|url=http://theindiandiaspora.com/news-details/diaspora-news/subprimary_news/gujarati-diaspora-has-contributed-to-gujarats-success.htm|website=theindiandiaspora.com|accessdate=22 October 2015|quote=According to him "It was a very warm discussion. PM Modi knows Canada well because we have been such active participants in Vibrant Gujarat for over 18 years now. He also knows very well how strong the Gujarati diaspora is in Canada. It may be up to one quarter of all the Indo-Canadians in this country, and so their success has been part of Gujarat's success." And "the prime minister (of India) recognizes that," Alexander stated emphatically.}}</ref>

Notable Gujarati Canadians include [[Bharat Masrani]] (CEO of [[Toronto-Dominion Bank|TD Bank Group]]),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.td.com/about-tdbfg/corporate-information/executive-profiles/group-heads/|title=Executive Profiles - Group Heads {{!}} TD Bank Group|website=www.td.com|language=en|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> [[Zain Verjee]] ([[CNN]] journalist),<ref>{{cite web|title=Zain Verjee – Atlanta, Georgia|url=https://alusainc.wordpress.com/2008/01/04/zain-verjee-washington-dc/|website=alusainc.wordpress.com|accessdate=7 December 2015|quote=Verjee also has produced successful radio campaigns spreading awareness of HIV/AIDS, road safety and violence against women. Her community efforts include work with Street Children and with Operation Smile. Verjee received her undergraduate degree in English from McGill University in Montreal and studied at York University in Canada. She speaks Gujarati, Kiswahili and conversational French.}}</ref> [[Ali Velshi]] (former [[CNN]], current [[MSNBC]] journalist),<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://alivelshi.com/|title=The Velshi Exchange|website=alivelshi.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref> [[Rizwan Manji]] (Canadian actor), [[Avan Jogia]] (Canadian actor<ref>https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Avan_Jogia</ref>), [[Richie Mehta]] (Canadian film director), [[Nazneen Contractor]] (Canadian actress), [[Ishu Patel]] ([[BAFTA]]-winning Animations director), [[Arif Virani]] (Member of Parliament for Parkdale-High Park),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/federal-election/federal-ridings-toronto-gta/2015/10/19/arif-virani-wins-in-parkdale-high-park.html|title=Arif Virani wins in Parkdale-High Park {{!}} The Star|work=thestar.com|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en}}</ref> [[Rahim Jaffer]] (Member of Parliament for Edmonton-Strathcona),<ref>{{cite web|title=Canada’s Prime Minister Stephen Harper is not a real Evangelical Christian|url=https://thenonconformer.wordpress.com/tag/rahim-jaffer/|website=the nonconformer.wordpress.com|accessdate=7 December 2015|quote=Jaffer, who is an Ismaili Muslim of Gujarati origin, became Canada’s youngest non-white MP at the age of 25 in 1997. He served four terms till his loss in the 2008 parliamentary elections.}}</ref> [[Naheed Nenshi]] (36th Mayor of Calgary),<ref>{{cite web|title=The Genius of Naheed Nenshi|url=http://www.glenpearson.ca/2014/02/the-genius-of-naheed-nenshi/|website=The Parallel Parliament|date=19 February 2014|quote=But there was more. In two words, he was challenging and electric. And his own background is so varied as to make him unique. He’s an east Indian who lived in Tanzania prior to coming to Canada. He’s slightly over 40 years of age, a Muslim, has a degree from Harvard, and just happened to best three solid status quo challengers to win Calgary’s top job. Seated together at the front of that assembly room, I realized it was the very mystique about him that caused people to look at things in a new fashion.}}</ref> [[Omar Sachedina]] ([[CTV News]] anchor)<ref>{{cite web|title=Omar Sachedina|url=http://www.ctvnews.ca/ctv-national-team/omar-sachedina-1.310948|website=ctvnews.ca|accessdate=7 December 2015|quote=Sachedina speaks French, Gujarati, and Kutchi. He enjoys travelling, music, and sampling food from around the world}}</ref> and [[Prashant Pathak]] (Investor and Philanthropist).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rhcapitalpartners.com/team_pathak.html|title=Our Team: Prashant Pathak - ReichmannHauer Capital Partners|website=www.rhcapitalpartners.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>

===East Africa===
Former British colonies in East Africa had many residents of [[South Asian]] descent. The primary immigration was mainly from Gujarat and to a lesser extent from Punjab. They were brought there by the [[British Empire]] from [[British India|India]] to do [[clerk|clerical]] work in Imperial service, or unskilled/semi-skilled manual labour such as construction or farm work. In the 1890s, 32,000 labourers from British India were brought to the then British East African colonies under indentured labour contracts to work on the construction of the [[Uganda Railway]] that started in the Kenyan port city of [[Mombasa]] and ended in [[Kisumu]] on Kenyan side of [[Lake Victoria]]. Most of the surviving Indians returned home, but 6,724 individuals decided to remain in the [[African Great Lakes]] after the line's completion.

Many Asians, particularly the Gujarati, in these regions were in the trading businesses. They included Gujaratis of all religions as well many of the castes and Quoms. Since the representation of Indians in these occupations was high, stereotyping of Indians in Kenya, Uganda and Tanganyka as shopkeepers was common. A number of people worked for the British run banks. They also worked in skilled labor occupations, as managers, teachers and administrators. Gujarati and other South Asians had significant influence on the economy, constituting 1% of the population while receiving a fifth of the national income. For example, in Uganda, the [[Nanji Kalidas Mehta|Mehta]] and [[Muljibhai Madhvani|Madhvani]] families controlled the bulk of the manufacturing businesses. Gated ethnic communities served elite healthcare and schooling services. Additionally, the tariff system in Uganda had historically been oriented toward the economic interests of South Asian traders.<ref name="Journal of Modern African Studies">{{cite book|title= JSTOR}}<[https://www.jstor.org/discover/10.2307/160072?uid=3739936&uid=2129&uid=2&uid=70&uid=4&uid=3739256&sid=21101589093047 Expulsion of a minority: essays on Ugandan Asians.]></ref> One of the oldest Jain overseas diaspora was of Gujarat. Their number was estimated at 45,000 at the independence of the East African countries in the early 1960s.<ref name="google26">{{citation |last1=Gregory|first1=Robert G.|title=Quest for equality: Asian politics in East Africa, 1900-1967|date=1993|publisher=Orient Longman Limited|location=New Delhi|isbn=0-863-11-208-0|page=26|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=Vl8tMabf5KUC&oi=fnd&pg=PA1 }}</ref> Most members of this community belonged to Gujarati speaking Halari Visa Oshwal Jain community originally from the [[Jamnagar]] area of [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]].<ref name="google26"/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mehta|first1=Makrand|title=Gujarati Business Communities in East African Diaspora: Major Historical Trends|journal=Economic and Political Weekly|date=2001|volume=36|issue=20|page=1738|jstor=4410637}}</ref>

The countries of East Africa gained independence from Britain in the early 1960s. At that time most Gujarati and other Asians opted to remain as British Subjects. The African politicians at that time accused Asians of economic exploitation and introduced a policy of Africanization. The 1968 Committee on "Africanisation in Commerce and Industry" in Uganda made far-reaching Indophobic proposals. A system of work permits and trade licenses was introduced in 1969 to restrict the role of Indians in economic and professional activities. Indians were segregated and discriminated against in all walks of life.<ref name="Amin-Indophobia">{{cite journal |title=General Amin and the Indian Exodus from Uganda |first=Hasu H. |last=Patel |journal=Issue: A Journal of Opinion |volume=2 |issue=4 |year=1972 |pages=12–22 |doi=10.2307/1166488 }}</ref> During the middle of the 1960s many Asians saw the writing on the wall and started moving either to UK or India. However, restrictive British immigration policies stopped a mass exodus of East African Asians until Idi Amin came to power in 1971. He exploited pre-existing Indophobia and spread propaganda against Indians involving stereotyping and scapegoating the Indian minority. Indians were stereotyped as "only traders" and "inbred" to their profession. Indians were labelled as "dukawallas" (an occupational term that degenerated into an anti-Indian slur during Amin's time), and stereotyped as "greedy, conniving", without any racial identity or loyalty but "always cheating, conspiring and plotting" to subvert Uganda. Amin used this propaganda to justify a campaign of "de-Indianization", eventually resulting in the expulsion and ethnic cleansing of Uganda's Indian minority.<ref name="Amin-Indophobia"/>

====Kenya====
Gujarati and other Indians started moving to the Kenya colony at the end of the 19th century when the British colonial authorities started opening up the country with the laying down of the Railways. A small colony of merchants, however, had existed on the port cities such Mombasa on the Kenyan coast for hundreds of years prior to that.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Parth Shastri|title=US researcher looks for Gujarati influence in Kenya and East Africa|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/US-researcher-looks-for-Gujarati-influence-in-Kenya-and-East-Africa/articleshow/46816299.cms|website=the times of india|accessdate=28 October 2015|quote=During British ascendancy, the early Gujarati-speaking traders were predominantly Muslims—Khoja, Bhora, and Ithna Asheri. They were quickly followed by Patel, Lohana, Bhatia and Oshawal. "Community was a major factor. It both energized Indian identity and simultaneously prevented Indians from coming together as a political whole except in times of dire crisis," Misha says.}}</ref> The immigrants who arrived with the British were the first ones to open up businesses in rural Kenya a century ago. These Dukawalas or shopkeepers were mainly Gujarati (Mostly Jains and Hindus and a minority of Muslims). Over the following decades the population, mainly Gujarati but also a sizable number of Punjabi, increased in size. The population started declining after the independence of Kenya in the 1960s. At that time the majority of Gujaratis opted for British citizenship and eventually moved there, especially to cities like [[Leicester]] or [[London]] suburbs. Famous Kenyans of Gujarati heritage who contributed greatly to the development of East Africa include [[Thakkar Bapa]], [[Manu Chandaria]],<ref name="premchand">{{cite news| title=Forbes India Magazine – Experiences of the Indian Diaspora in Africa| date=26 August 2009| url=http://business.in.com/article/magazine-extra/experiences-of-the-indian-diaspora-in-africa/3762/0}}</ref> [[Atul Shah]], [[Baloobhai Patel]],<ref>{{cite web|title=The rise and rise of Kenya's silent billionaires at NSE|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Low-profile-billionaires-raise-their-stake-at-Nairobi-bourse-/-/539552/1905312/-/item/1/-/afc8m7z/-/index.html|website=Business daily Africa|accessdate=7 February 2015|quote=Baloobhai Patel, a director of Pan Africa Insurance, is invariably listed as one of the largest individual shareholders of more than 10 companies on the Nairobi bourse. The 75-year-old has major interests in Pan Africa Insurance, Barclays, Bamburi, DTB, Mumias Sugar, and Safaricom currently valued at Sh2.4 billion.}}</ref> [[Bhimji Depar Shah]] (Forbes),<ref>{{cite web|title=Vimal replaced on Forbes list of Africa's 50 richest people|url=http://www.businessdailyafrica.com/Forbes-names-Africa-s-richest-in-2014/-/539444/2528178/-/7vrdpf/-/index.html|website=Business daily Africa|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> [[Naushad Merali]] (Forbes),<ref>[http://www.kenyanentrepreneur.com/naushad-merali-who-is-this-man?cid=71065 ''Maybe he is a Patel, I hear Indian …''] at Kenyan Entrepreneur</ref> and Indian philanthropist, [[Alibhai Mulla Jeevanjee]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Saeed Khan|title=Gujaratis brought glory to East Africa|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/Gujaratis-brought-glory-to-East-Africa/articleshow/23106715.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=7 February 2015|quote=Historian Makrand Mehta credits Gujaratis' contribution for the success of this project. He describes how A M Jeevanji, a Dawoodi Bohra from Kutch, got labour contract for the project.}}</ref> who played a large role in the development of modern-day Kenya during colonial rule.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Bharat Yagnik,|title=Non-Resident Gujaratis build Rs 100cr hospital in Nairobi|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/Non-Resident-Gujaratis-build-Rs-100cr-hospital-in-Nairobi/articleshow/49546219.cms|website=the times of India|accessdate=1 November 2015|quote=Even as the India-Africa Forum Summit 2015 kicked off celebrating Indo-Africa ties, the Kutchi Leuva Patel Samaj settled in Kenya is building a super-speciality charitable hospital at the cost of Rs 100 crore in Nairobi to gift a state-of-art healthcare facility to locals...Lakshman Raghwani, a Nairobi-based contractor and community leader, said the community is running a school for 22 years in Nairobi that has over 3,000 Indian and Kenyan students. "The hospital is an extension of our engagement with the local community.Two other major hospitals on national level - MP Shah Hospital in Nairobi and Agha Khan Hospital in Mombasa - also have Gujarati connection," he said.}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author1=Bharat Yagnik,|title=From assistant priest to Kenya's steel tycoon|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/nri/nri-achievers/From-assistant-priest-to-Kenyas-steel-tycoon/articleshow/48120673.cms|website=the times of India|accessdate=1 November 2015|quote=He has earned the sobriquet 'Guru' amongst his peers in Kenya. With a net worth of $650 million, Gujarati steel tycoon Narendra Raval (53) of Devki Group is one of the wealthiest businessmen of Kenya today. Narendra Raval, through his pragmatic business ideologies and philanthropy, aims to transform the once-hostile perception of Africans about Indian businessmen. His company employs 98% staff from local Kenyan and African populace and also runs many orphanages and schools for the underprivileged.}}</ref>

====Uganda====
{{Main|Indians in Uganda}}
There is a small community of people of Indian origin living in Uganda, but the community is far smaller than before 1972 when Ugandan ruler Idi Amin expelled most Asians, including Gujaratis.<ref>{{cite web|title=Ugandan Asians are part of Britain's secret weapon for success|url=http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2012/12/ugandan-asians-are-part-of-britains-secret-weapon-for-success/|website=spectator.co.uk|accessdate=28 October 2015|quote=In 1997, Ugandan President Museveni invited the displaced Asians to return home. And while some returned to sort out their affairs, very few went back for good.|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151110012925/http://blogs.new.spectator.co.uk/2012/12/ugandan-asians-are-part-of-britains-secret-weapon-for-success/|archivedate=10 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In the late 19th century, mostly [[Sikhs]], were brought on three-year contracts, with the aid of Imperial British contractor [[Alibhai Mulla Jeevanjee]] to build the [[Uganda Railway]] from Mombasa to Kisumu by 1901, and to [[Kampala]] by 1931. Some died, while others returned to India after the end of their contracts, but few chose to stay. They were joined by Gujarati traders called "passenger Indians",<ref>{{cite web|last=Hiralal|first=Kalpana|title=Indian Family Businesses in Natal, 1870–1950|url=http://natalia.org.za/Files/38/Natalia%2038%20pp27-37%20C.pdf|publisher=Natal Society Foundation|accessdate=2010}}</ref> both Hindu and Muslim free migrants who came to serve the economic needs of the indentured labourers, and to capitalise on the economic opportunities.

After the 1972 expulsion, most Indians and Gujaratis migrated to the United Kingdom. Due to the efforts of the [[Aga Khan]], many Khoja Nizari Ismaili refugees from Uganda were offered asylum in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Out of Africa: Thousands of Ismaili Muslims expelled from their African homelands in the 1970s have thrived in Canada|url=http://www.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/observer/story.html?id=4d43f2e2-2ccf-4234-96f4-35e853c20679|website=www.canada.com|publisher=Calgary Herald|accessdate=28 October 2015|quote=Through the efforts of the Aga Khan, other countries agreed to take in the refugees, and they were scattered over the world. Britain took in 20,000, the U.S. took 50,000, and 75,000 came to Canada... Ladha said Canada's role in taking in the refugees has earned the praise of the Aga Khan for its treatment of refugees and its multiculturalism. "The Aga Khan is a great admirer of Canada's multicultural policies," said Ladha. As a result, he's putting $4 million toward a global centre for pluralism in Ottawa, with the Canadian government providing $3 million..|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117035913/http://www.canada.com/calgaryherald/news/observer/story.html?id=4d43f2e2-2ccf-4234-96f4-35e853c20679|archivedate=17 January 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

====Tanzania====
{{Main|Indians in Tanzania}}
Indians have a long history in [[Tanzania]] starting with the arrival of Gujarati traders in the 19th century.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Anna Greenwood|author2=Harshad Topiwala|title=Indian Doctors in Kenya, 1895-1940: The Forgotten History Cambridge Imperial and Post-Colonial Studies Series|date=2015|publisher=Palgrave Macmillan|page=25|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=r5gMCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25&lpg=PA25&dq=gujaratis,+kenya&source=bl&ots=NihuQa9YsN&sig=kCj-XbFgRHKI9Z88eP5jBzER5mE&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDkQ6AEwBTgKahUKEwiSgOew1uXIAhUFVD4KHb6hDjY#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20kenya&f=false|quote=The Gujaratis comprised a large number of the traders drawn from the Western Indian port province of Gujarat (including Kutch) who had had long historical trading links with Zanzibar. Their presence meant that from very early on Zanzibar became demographically colonised by a religiously and ethnically diverse Gujarati speaking population of Ismaili Khojas, Bhoras, Suni Memons, Hindu Vaniyas and the Parsis. Frustratingly for historians this group of immigrants left few records, but it is widely agreed that they were the ancestors of the communities of Indian traders that the British encountered when they arrived in Zanzibar and the East Coast of Africa at the end of the nineteenth century.}}</ref> There are currently over 50,000 people of Indian origin in Tanzania. Many of them are traders and they control a sizeable portion of the Tanzanian economy. They came to gradually control the trade in [[Zanzibar]]. Many of the buildings constructed then still remain in [[Stone Town]], the focal trading point on the island.

===South Africa===
[[File:Hashim Amla.jpg|thumb|[[Hashim Amla|Amla]] training with [[South Africa national cricket team|South Africa]] in 2009.]]
The Indian community in South Africa is more than a century old and is concentrated in and around the city of [[Durban]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Robin David|title=Rainbow Nation's colourful Indians|url=http://blogs.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/On-the-bounce/rainbow-nation-s-colourful-indians/|website=Times of India|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=July 4, 2010|quote=Gujaratis of Durban, who came to South Africa mainly from Surat and Saurashtra, have gone a step further and are keeping their unique Gujarati identity alive as well. Most of them arrived as traders soon after the first Indian labourers were brought in to work on sugarcane fields in the 1860s and have carved out a unique niche for themselves.}}</ref> The vast majority of immigrant pioneer Gujaratis who came in the latter half of the 19th century were ''passenger Indians'' who paid for their own travel fare and means of transport to arrive and settle South Africa, in pursuit of fresh trade and career opportunities and as such were treated as [[British subject]]s, unlike the fate of a class of Indian indentured laborours who were transported to work on the sugarcane plantations of [[Natal Colony]] in dire conditions. Passenger Indians, who initially operated in Durban, expanded inland, to the South African Republic ([[South African Republic|Transvaal]]), establishing communities in settlements on the main road between [[Johannesburg]] and Durban. After wealthy [[Gujarati Muslim]] merchants began experiencing discrimination from repressive colonial legislation in [[Colony of Natal|Natal]],<ref name="saHistoryIndianTimeline">{{cite web |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/chronology/special-chrono/governance/indian-history.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110606163436/http://www.sahistory.org.za/pages/chronology/special-chrono/governance/indian-history.html|archivedate=6 June 2011 |title=Timeline|accessdate=2011-11-24}}</ref> they sought the help of one young lawyer, [[Mahatma Gandhi]] to represent the case of a [[Umar Hajee Ahmed Jhaveri|Memon]] businessman. [[Umar Hajee Ahmed Jhaveri]] was consequently elected the first president of the [[South African Indian Congress]].

Indians have played an important role in the [[anti-apartheid movement]] of South Africa.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mehta|first1=edited by Nalin|last2=Mehta|first2=Mona G.|title=Gujarat beyond Gandhi identity, society and conflict|date=2011|publisher=Routledge|location=London|isbn=1317988353|page=161|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=NfraAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA161&dq=gujaratis,+indian+independence&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi7-vGn0tbJAhVImBoKHfX9DWcQ6AEIVTAI#v=onepage&q=gujaratis%2C%20indian%20independence&f=false|accessdate=12 December 2015|quote=Mobility remains a feature of Gujaratis. While apartheid may have sought to keep people in a mould, Gujaratis kept resisting this through their caste, class, and national mobility.}}</ref> Many were incarcerated alongside [[Nelson Mandela]] following the [[Rivonia Trial]], and many became martyred fighting to end racial discrimination. Notable South African Indians of Gujarati heritage include [[Marxist]] freedom fighters such as [[Ahmed Timol]] (activist),<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/people/ahmed-timol |title=Ahmed Timol &#124; South African History Online |publisher=Sahistory.org.za |date= |accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref> [[Yusuf Dadoo]] (activist),<ref>{{cite web|title=Yusuf Dadoo: A Biography|url=http://www.v1.sahistory.org.za/pages/people/bios/dadoo,y.htm|website=sahistory.org.za|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref> [[Ahmed Kathrada]] (activist),<ref>{{cite web|title=Indian-origin anti-apartheid activist Ahmed Kathrada pays tribute to Nelson Mandela|url=http://articles.economictimes.indiatimes.com/2013-12-06/news/44865536_1_nelson-mandela-foundation-mentor-collective-leadership|website=The Economic Times|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=Dec 6, 2013}}</ref> [[Amina Cachalia]] (activist) and [[Dullah Omar]] (activist),<ref>{{cite web|title=South African leader of Indian origin dead|url=http://www.thehindu.com/2004/03/14/stories/2004031401320900.htm|website=The Hindu|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> as well as [[Ahmed Deedat]] (missionary), [[Imran Garda]] (Al Jazeera English) and [[Hashim Amla]] (cricketer).<ref>{{cite web|author1=MARK HAYES|title=The many faces of top South African batsman Hashim Amla|url=http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/cricket/the-many-faces-of-top-south-african-batsman-hashim-amla/story-e6frg26c-1226509433207?nk=130041c5b3766c4c13bf44075373e44b|archive-url=https://archive.is/20150208025506/http://www.perthnow.com.au/sport/cricket/the-many-faces-of-top-south-african-batsman-hashim-amla/story-e6frg26c-1226509433207?nk=130041c5b3766c4c13bf44075373e44b|dead-url=yes|archive-date=8 February 2015|accessdate=5 February 2015|quote=His parents are South African-born, but his grandparents were indentured workers from Surat -- and the family still occasionally speaks Gujarati from that western Indian region.}}</ref>

===Sultanate of Oman===
{{Main|Indians in Oman}}
[[Oman]], holding a strategically important position at the mouth of the [[Persian Gulf]], has been the primary focus of trade and commerce for medieval Gujarati merchants for much of its glorious history and Gujaratis, along with various other ethnic groups, contributed to the rich dynamic culture, founding and settlement of its capital port city, [[Muscat, Oman|Muscat]].<ref>{{cite web|author1=Willem Floor|title=The Persian Gulf: Muscat – City, Society and Trade|url=http://www.magepublishers.com/persian-gulf-muscat-city-society-trade/|website=Mage Publishers|accessdate=5 February 2015|quote=Muscat, the capital city of present day Oman, has had a long, and colorful history as a typical Indian Ocean port at the mouth of the Persian Gulf. International trade brought about a rich mix of various ethnic and religious groups including, besides Arabs, Africans, Baluchis, Mekranis, Sindis, Gujaratis, Persians and many others. At the turn of the twentieth century fourteen languages could be heard spoken in the city.}}</ref> Some of the earliest Indian immigrants to settle in Oman were the [[Bhatia caste|Bhatia]]s of [[Kutch]], who have a powerful presence in Oman dating back to the 16th century.<ref>{{cite book|author1=Khalid M. Al-Azri|title=Social and Gender Inequality in Oman: The Power of Religious and Political Tradition.|date=2013|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-67241-2|page=50|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=eb6Pgy1Q0vQC&pg=PA50&dq=bhatias,+oman&hl=en&sa=X&ei=xbLTVJ-SD8T7UJy6gLgE&ved=0CD8Q6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=bhatias%2C%20oman&f=false|accessdate=5 February 2015|quote=Hindus had settled in Oman by the sixteenth century, and from at least the early nineteenth century Omani commerce and trade has been conducted by Hindu Banyans of Bhatia caste deriving from Kutch in Gujarat.}}</ref> At the turn of the 19th century, Gujaratis wielded such immense political clout that [[Faisal bin Turki, Sultan of Muscat and Oman|Faisal bin Turki]], the great-grandfather of the current ruler, spoke Gujarati and [[Swahili language|Swahili]] along with his native Arabic<ref>{{cite web|author1=Hugh Eakin|title=In the Heart of Mysterious Oman|url=http://www.nybooks.com/articles/archives/2014/aug/14/heart-mysterious-oman/|website=The New York Review of Books|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=August 14, 2014}}</ref> and Oman's sultan Syed Said (1791-1856) was persuaded to shift his capital from Muscat to [[Zanzibar]], more than two thousand miles from the Arabian mainland, on the recommendation of Shivji Topan and Bhimji families who lent money to the Sultan.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Bharat Yagnik|title=Oman was Gujaratis' first stop in their world sweep|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Oman-was-Gujaratis-first-stop-in-their-world-sweep/articleshow/45737586.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=Jan 3, 2015}}</ref> In modern times, business tycoon Kanaksi Khimji, from the famous Khimji family of Gujarat<ref>{{cite book|author1=Marc Valeri|title=Oman : politics and society in the Qaboos state|date=2009|publisher=C. Hurst|location=London|isbn=978-1-85065-933-4|page=42|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MKzlyho2KQkC&pg=PA42&dq=khimji+family,+gujarat&hl=en&sa=X&ei=as3TVIL1C4z_UJD8gDA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=khimji%20family%2C%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=5 February 2015|quote=One of these families is another Banyan one, known today as Khimji, whose ancestor came to Oman around 1870 from Gujarat. The family business grew during the Second World War, when it became the Sultan's most important contractor: the Khimji group was the exclusive supplier of the royal palace, and was granted the monopoly and distribution of food products in the Dhofar region.}}</ref> was conferred title of [[Sheikh]] by the Sultan, the first ever use of the title for a member of the Hindu community.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Runa Mukherjee Parikh|title=World's only Hindu Sheikh traces his roots to Gujarat|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/Worlds-only-Hindu-Sheikh-traces-his-roots-to-Gujarat/articleshow/19995680.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=5 February 2015|date=May 11, 2013|quote="We see achievements as milestones in the quest for excellence. We just want to be the best," says the 77-year-old tycoon, Kanaksi Khimji. Not sales and volumes, Khimji believes that the most important measure of success for his family's business is how far it has helped advance the national development plans laid out by Oman's Sultan Qaboos bin Said. In fact, Khimji with his Indian roots was one of the first to embrace Omanisation, a directive to train and empower Omani professionals. Such a rare honour makes Khimji the most distinguished Indian in this Middle Eastern country.}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Alpers|first1=Edward A.|title=The Indian Ocean in World History|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780199721795|page=106|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=suLQCwAAQBAJ&pg=PA106&dq=gujarati,+oman&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=gujarati%2C%20oman&f=false|language=en|quote=Gujarati merchants enjoyed a special place in the political economy of an emerging Omani Empire in the Western Indian Ocean, while as British-protected subjects they became the advance guard of British imperial presence in both the Gulf and eastern Africa north of the Portuguese possessions. Already by this time Omani customs collection, which was farmed out on five-year contracts to the highest bidder, was in the hands of a Kachchhi Hindu trader named Mowjee Bhimani whose family maintained control of the Masqat farm into the 1840s.}}</ref> The Muscati Mahajan is one of the oldest merchants associations founded more than a century ago.<ref>{{cite web|title=Muscat Early History|url=http://www.bhatiamahajan.com/muscat--middle-east.html|website=bhatia mahajan|accessdate=5 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Hoerder|first1=Dirk|title=Migrations and Belongings|publisher=Harvard University Press|isbn=9780674281318|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=2BahAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA106&dq=GUJARATIS,+ECONOMIC+MIGRATIONS&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=GUJARATIS%2C%20ECONOMIC%20MIGRATIONS&f=false|language=en|quote=The Western trade had, for example, led to settlement of merchants from the Gulf of Kutch and from Jamnagar in Zanzibar. In view of local hostility to intermingling, the merchants brought in wives, and a community emerged by 1860s. Its five to six thousand Hindus and Muslims fragmented, however, along ethnoreligious and occupational lines: Baluchi as soldiers of the Omani sultan, Memons from Sind in shipping and fishing, Parsi merchants, Hindu trading castes - Baniyas, Bhatias, Lohanas, and Shia Muslims, as well as Daudi Bohoras, Ismaili Khojas, Isthnasteris, and Goan Catholics. Ethnoreligious-professional traditions framed agency: Hindus usually returned when they had accumulated savings and wealth, whereas Muslims stayed and formed families... In the frame of dependencies between colonizer and colonies, the Gujarati enclave, protected by the Omani sultanate, did in the 1870s, become a conduit for British influence and, over time for British ascendancy. Distinct vertical links of each of the South Asian ethnoreligious groups to the British in Mumbai hindered horizontal Indian-cultured homogenization in the community. Mumbai's commercial expansion resulted in increased Gujarati in-migration, and Gujarati became the community's lingua franca. The privileged and thus distinct status granted by the Omani sultanate prevented indigenization.}}</ref>

===Southeast Asia===
Gujaratis had a flourishing trade with Southeast Asia in the 15th and 16th centuries, and played a pivotal role in establishing [[Islam]] in the region.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gujarat helped establish Islam in SE Asia|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/ahmedabad/ampnbspGujarat-helped-establish-Islam-in-SE-Asia/articleshow/11262585.cms|publisher=[[The Times of India]]|last=Prabhune|first=Tushar|location=[[Ahmedabad]]|date=December 27, 2011}}</ref> Miller (2010) presented a theory that the indigenous scripts of [[Sumatra]] ([[Indonesia]]), [[Sulawesi]] (Indonesia) and the [[Philippines]] are descended from an early form of the Gujarati script. [[Tomé Pires]] reported a presence of a thousand Gujaratis in [[Malacca]] ([[Malaysia]]) prior to 1512.<ref name="Miller2010">{{cite journal|last1=Miller|first1=Christopher|title=A Gujarati Origin for Scripts of Sumatra, Sulawesi and the Philippines|journal=Annual Meeting of the Berkeley Linguistics Society|volume=36|issue=1|year=2010|pages=276|issn=2377-1666|doi=10.3765/bls.v36i1.3917}}</ref>Gujarati language continues to be spoken in Singapore and Malaysia.<ref name=e20/><ref name="pr">{{Cite web|url=http://www.pressreader.com/malaysia/the-sun-malaysia/20150225/281831462182561|title=PressReader.com - Connecting People Through News|website=www.pressreader.com|access-date=2018-06-29}}</ref>

====Malaysia====
{{Main|Gujarati Malaysian}}
There estimated around 31,500 Gujarati in Malaysia. Most of this community work as traders and settled in urban part of Malaysia like Georgetown, Kuala Lumpur and Ipoh.<ref name=pr/>

==Cuisine==
{{Main|Gujarati cuisine}}
[[File:Vedhmi.jpg|thumb|right|upright=0.9|''Vedhmi'' is a sweet lentil stuffed [[Roti|chapatis]].]]
Gujarati food has famously been described as "the haute cuisine of vegetarianism" and meals have a subtle balance of sweet, tart and mild hot sensations on the palate.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Jung|first1=Jeffrey Aldford & Naomi Duguid ; photographs by Jeffrey Aldford & Naomi Duguid ; additional photographs by Richard|title=Mangoes & curry leaves culinary travels through the great subcontinent|date=2005|publisher=Artisan|location=New York|isbn=9781579655655|page=14|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=K5viC1KaoBUC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=meat+eating+in+gujarat&source=bl&ots=VQtpLa8cdw&sig=4Tf7YKiGITTzroUzqCj-zkK7WzQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDwQ6AEwBDgeahUKEwj6m-Pc1tvIAhWEuBQKHVYEDXE#v=onepage&q=meat%20eating%20in%20gujarat&f=false|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|author1=Dhwani Talati-Padiyar|title=TRAVELLED, TASTED, TRIED & TAILORED: Food Chronicles|publisher=Lulu publishers|page=76|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c0wiAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA76&dq=gujarati+cuisine,&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDEQ6AEwADgKahUKEwi21o_q2dvIAhWDvhQKHRiXDak#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20cuisine%2C&f=false|accessdate=24 October 2015}}</ref> Gujarati Jains, many Hindus and [[Buddhist]] in Gujarat are vegetarian. However, many Gujaratis such as Hindu [[Rajput]]s, [[Christian]]s, and Muslims have traditionally eaten a variety of meats and seafood, although [[Muslim]]s don't eat pork and Hindus don't eat beef.<ref>{{cite web|author1=[[The Racist Sandwich|Zahir Janmohamed]]|title=Butter Chicken in Ahmedabad|url=http://india.blogs.nytimes.com/2013/08/20/butter-chicken-in-ahmedabad/|website=nytimes|accessdate=24 October 2015|quote=But attitudes are changing, according to Mr. Dauwa. "More people, especially businessmen from China and Japan, are visiting Gujarat and many of them want non-vegetarian food," he said. "And also, Gujaratis are becoming wealthier, and when they live abroad they pick up nonvegetarian eating habits."}}</ref> [[Gujarati cuisine]] follows the traditional Indian full meal structure of rice, cooked vegetables, [[dal|lentil dal]] or curry and ''[[roti]]''. The different types of flatbreads that a Gujarati cooks are rotli or [[chapati]], [[Bhakri|bhakhri]], thepla or dhebara, [[puri]], maal purah, and puran-pohli. Popular snacks such as [[Khaman]], [[Dhokla]], [[Pani Puri]], Dhokli, dal-dhokli, [[Undhiyu]], [[Jalebi]], fafda, [[Chevda|chevdoh]], [[Samosa]], [[papri chaat]], Muthia, Bhajia, Patra, bhusu, locho, sev {{Not a typo|usal}}, fafda gathiya, vanela gathiya and [[Sev mamra]] are traditional Gujarati dishes savoured by many communities across the world.<ref>{{cite web|title=Western Indian Food: An explosion of Flavour|url=http://blog.mapsofindia.com/india/western-indian-food-an-explosion-of-flavour/|website=mapsofindia|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>

[[Khichdi]] – a mix of rice and [[mung dal]], cooked with spice – is a popular and nutritious dish which has regional variations. Quite often the khichdi is accompanied by [[Kadhi]]. It is found satisfying by most Gujaratis, and cooked very regularly in most homes, typically on a busy day due to its ease of cooking. It can also become an elaborate meal such as a [[thali]] when served with several other side dishes such as a vegetable curry, yogurt, [[sabji|sabzi]] shaak, onions, mango pickle and [[papad]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hajratwala|first1=Bhanu|title=Gujarati kitchen : family recipes for the global palate|date=2011|publisher=Westland|location=Bangalore|isbn=9789380658490|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vTjBfwzuEYgC&printsec=frontcover&dq=gujarati+food+khichdi&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CC0Q6AEwAWoVChMIlKGTqp_eyAIVQ3EUCh3t1wTl#v=onepage&q&f=false}}</ref>

Spices have traditionally been made on grinding stones, however, since villages have seen rapid growth and industrialization in recent decades, today people may use a blender or grinder. People from north Gujarat use dry red chili powder, whereas people from south Gujarat prefer using green chili and coriander in their cooking. There is no standard recipe for Gujarati dishes, however the use of tomatoes and [[lemons]] is a consistent theme throughout Gujarat.<ref name="10 Best Gujarati Recipes">{{cite web|title=10 Best Gujarati Recipes|url=http://food.ndtv.com/lists/10-best-gujarati-recipes-695837|website=ndtv.com|accessdate=27 October 2015}}</ref>
Traditionally Gujaratis eat [[mukhwas]] at the end of a meal to enhance digestion, and desserts such as ''aam shrikhand'' made using [[mango]] salad and hung [[curd]] are very popular.<ref name="10 Best Gujarati Recipes"/> In many parts of Gujarat, drinking [[chaas]] (chilled [[buttermilk]]) or soda after lunch or dinner is also quite common.

Surti delicasies include [[ghari (sweet)|ghari]] which is a [[puri]] filled with [[khoa]] and nuts that is typically eaten during the festival [[Chandani Padva]]. [[Khambhat]] delicacies include famous [[sutarfeni]] – made from fine strands of sweet dough (rice or maida) garnished with pistachios, and ''halwasan'' which are hard squares made from broken wheat, khoa, nutmeg and [[pistachios]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Darra Goldstein|title=The Oxford Companion to Sugar and Sweets Oxford Companions Series|date=2015|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=0199313393|page=358|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jbi6BwAAQBAJ&pg=PA358&dq=gujarat,+cornstarch,+custard&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCgQ6AEwAGoVChMI1vysq6LeyAIVgR0-Ch23hwIs#v=onepage&q=gujarat%2C%20cornstarch%2C%20custard&f=false}}</ref> A version of English [[custard]] is made in Gujarat that uses [[cornstarch]] instead of the traditional eggs. It is cooked with cardamom and [[saffron]], and served with fruit and sliced almonds.<ref>{{cite web|title=Sitafal basundi|url=http://www.khanakhazana.com/recipes/view.aspx?id=6361|website=khana khazana|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref> Gujarati families celebrate [[Sharad Purnima]] by having dinner with doodh-pauva under moonlight.<ref>{{cite book|title=Passing on the Culture in the Diaspora: Inter-generational Communication of Cultural Identity Amongst Gujaratis in the USA.|date=2007|publisher=ProQuest|page=113|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j5n5JDDhCZkC&pg=PA113&dq=gujarati+food,+doodh+pauva&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CDIQ6AEwAGoVChMIr-Wg85_eyAIVAW0-Ch3ZUgU8#v=onepage&q=gujarati%20food%2C%20doodh%20pauva&f=false|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Doodh Poha on Sharad Poonam|url=http://flat-footedfoodies.blogspot.co.uk/2011/10/doodh-pauva-poha-on-sharad-poonam.html|website=Flat Footed Foodies|accessdate=25 October 2015}}</ref>

==Literature==
{{main|Gujarati literature|}}
[[File:Guj Script Mahatma Gandhi 1.png|thumb|upright=0.95|Excerpt from "[[My experiments with truth]]" - the [[autobiography]] of [[Mahatma Gandhi]] in its original Gujarati.]]
The history of [[Gujarati literature]] may be traced to 1000 AD. Since then literature has flourished till date. Well known laureates of Gujarati literature are [[Jhaverchand Meghani]], [[Avinash Vyas]], [[Hemchandracharya]], [[Narsinh Mehta]], [[Gulabdas Broker]], [[Akho]], [[Premanand Bhatt]], [[Shamal Bhatt]], [[Dayaram]], [[Dalpatram]], [[Narmad]], [[Govardhanram Tripathi]], Mahatma Gandhi, [[K. M. Munshi]], [[Umashankar Joshi]], [[Suresh Joshi]], [[Pannalal Patel]], Imamuddin khanji Babi Saheb (Ruswa mazlumi), [[Niranjan Bhagat]], [[Rajendra Keshavlal Shah]], [[Raghuveer Chaudhari]] and [[Sitanshu Yashaschandra|Sitanshu Yashaschandra Mehta]].

[[Kavi Kant]], [[Kalapi]] and [[Mareez|Abbas Abdulali Vasi]] are Gujarati language poets. [[Ardeshar Khabardar]], Gujarati-speaking Parsi who was president of [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] was a nationalist poet. His poem, ''Jya Jya Vase Ek Gujarati, Tya Tya Sadakal Gujarat'' (Wherever a Gujarati resides, there forever is Gujarat) depicts Gujarati ethnic pride and is widely popular in Gujarat.<ref name="Williams1984">{{cite book|author=Raymond Brady Williams|title=A New Face of Hinduism: The Swaminarayan Religion|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AHI7AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA170|accessdate=18 August 2014|year=1984|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=978-0-521-27473-9|pages=170–}}</ref>

[[Gujarat Vidhya Sabha]], [[Gujarat Sahitya Sabha]], and [[Gujarati Sahitya Parishad]] are Ahmedabad based literary institutions promoting the spread of Gujarati literature.
[[Saraswatichandra (novel)|Saraswatichandra]] is a novel by [[Govardhanram Tripathi]]. Writers like Harindra Dave, Suresh Dalal, Jyotindra Dave, [[Dinkar Joshi]], Prahlad Brahmbhatt, Tarak Mehta, Harkisan Mehta, [[Chandrakant Bakshi]], Vinod Bhatt, Kanti Bhatt, [[Makarand Dave]], and [[Varsha Adalja]] have influenced Gujarati thinkers.

[[Bhagwan Swaminarayan|Swaminarayan]] paramhanso, like Bramhanand, Premanand, contributed to Gujarati language literature with prose like [[Vachanamrut]] and poetry in the form of [[bhajans]]. [[Kanji Swami]] a spiritual mystic who was honored with the title, '[[Koh-i-noor]] of [[Kathiawar]]' made literary contributions to [[Jain]] philosophy and promoted [[Ratnatraya]].<ref>{{cite web|title=POOJYA GURUDEV SHREE KANJI SWAMI|url=http://www.mangalayatan.com/gurudevshri.html|website=mangalayatan.com|accessdate=19 November 2015|quote=He read many Shwetambar Scriptures and preached in so impressed way that people called him ‘KOHINOOR OF KATHIAWAD’|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151119223839/http://www.mangalayatan.com/gurudevshri.html|archivedate=19 November 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

Gujarati theatre owes a lot to bhavai. [[Bhavai]] is a musical performance of stage plays. Ketan Mehta and [[Sanjay Leela Bhansali]] explored artistic use of bhavai in films such as ''[[Bhavni Bhavai]]'', ''[[Oh Darling! Yeh Hai India]]'' and ''[[Hum Dil De Chuke Sanam]]''. Dayro (gathering) involves singing and conversation reflecting on human nature.

Gujarati language is enriched by the Adhyatmik literature written by the Jain scholar, [[Shrimad Rajchandra]] and Pandit Himmatlal Jethalal Shah. This literature is both in the form of poetry and prose.<ref>{{cite web|title=Shrimad Rajchandra – A spiritual gem|url=http://www.rajsaubhag.org/category/spiritual/foundations/shrimad-rajchandra/|website=www.rajsaubhag.org|accessdate=27 October 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140825134936/http://www.rajsaubhag.org/category/spiritual/foundations/shrimad-rajchandra/|archivedate=25 August 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>

== Gujarati folklore ==
Folklores are important part of Gujarati culture. The folktales of Kankavati are religious in nature because they sprung from the ordinary day-to-day human cycle of life independent of, and sometimes deviating from the scriptures. They are part of the Hindu rituals and practices for marriage,[[Simantonnayana|baby shower]] , [[naming ceremony]], the harvest and death, and are not merely religious acts but they reflect the lived life of people in rural and urban societies.The anthologies of [[Dadaji Ni Vato]] and Raang Chhe Barot are pragmatic with practical and the esoteric wisdom. Saurashtra Ni Rasdhar is a collection of love legends and depicts every shade of love and love is the main emotion which makes human world beautiful because it calls forth patience, responsibility, sense of commitment and dedication.Also the study of Meghani‘s works is quintessential because he was a trailblazer in exploring the vast unexplored heritage of Gujarati folklore. His folktales mirrors milieu of Gujarat, dialects, duhas, decors, humane values, sense of sacrifice and spirit of adventure, enthusiasm and, of course, the flaws in people. Meghani‘s folktales are verbal miniature of Gujarati culture.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Soni|first=vandana|date=2014|title=A Translation of Jhaverchand Meghani’s Nontranslated Folk Tales from Gujarati into English with a Critical Evaluation|url=http://shodhganga.inflibnet.ac.in/bitstream/10603/123916/11/11_chapter%206.pdf|journal=|volume=|pages=484|via=}}</ref>

