===Politicians===

Some of the most important figures involved in the independence movement were Gujarati. These include [[Mahatma Gandhi]], [[Sardar Patel]], and father of Pakistan [[Muhammad Ali Jinnah]]. Gujaratis have also been prime ministers of India. They include [[Morarji Desai]], and the current prime minister [[Narendra Modi]]. Others involved in Gujarat or Indian National politics include current former chief minister [[Anandiben Patel]], [[Rajesh Chudasama]], [[Shaktisinh Gohil]], [[Vitthal Radadiya]], [[Vasanbhai Ahir]], [[Purshottam Solanki]], [[Prabhatsinh Pratapsinh Chauhan]], [[Poonamben Madam]], [[Asifa Khan]], [[Vijay Rupani]], [[Dileepbhai Sanghani|Dileep Sanghani]], [[Jayantilal Bhanusali]], [[Arjun Modhwadia]], [[Kandhal Jadeja]] and [[Shankar Chaudhary]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shankar Chaudhary|url=https://www.facebook.com/ShankarChaudharyBJP|website=Facebook|accessdate=23 October 2015}}</ref>
There have been many Gujaratis involved in Pakistani politics, with the most prominent individuals being stateswoman and leading founder of Pakistan, [[Fatima Jinnah]]; the sixth [[Prime Minister of Pakistan]], [[I.I. Chundrigar]]; and the current [[Deputy Chairman of the Senate of Pakistan]], [[Saleem Mandviwalla]]. Other important Pakistani-Gujarati politicians include [[Mahmoud Haroon]], [[Hussain Haroon]], [[Muhammad Dilawar Khanji]], [[Zubeida Rahimtoola]], [[Ashraf W. Tabani]], [[Arshad Vohra]], [[Habib Rahimtoola]], and [[Abdul Qadir Patel]], as well as many others.. UK politicians of Gujarati descent include [[Meghnad Desai, Baron Desai|Baron Desai]], [[Dolar Popat|Baron Popat]], [[Rumi Verjee|Baron Verjee]], [[Navnit Dholakia, Baron Dholakia|Baron Dholakia]], [[Bhikhu Parekh|Baron Parekh]], [[Shailesh Vara]], and [[Priti Patel]], among others as well as Canadian politician [[Arif Virani]].

===Social activists===
[[Vikram Sarabhai]], [[Shrimad Rajchandra]], [[Swami Dayanand Saraswati]], [[Gopaldas Ambaidas Desai]], [[Ashoka Mehta]], [[Indulal Yagnik]], [[Sanat Mehta]], [[Ravi Shankar Vyas]], [[Jhaverchand Meghani]], [[Abbas Tyabji]], [[Mahadev Desai]], [[Jayanti Dalal]], [[Kanaiyalal Maneklal Munshi|K.M. Munshi]], [[Jugatram Dave]], [[Odhavram]], [[Shyamji Krishna Varma]], and [[S. R. Rana]].

===Arts and entertainment===
[[File:Navratri Garba.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|Women and men performing [[Garba (dance)|Garba]] as part of [[Navaratri]] celebrations in the city of Ahmedabad]]
[[File:Mer Dandiya.jpg|thumb|upright=1.15|[[Mer people|Mer]] [[Dandiya]], a sword dance performed by the martial communities of [[Saurashtra (region)|Saurashtra]]]]

Famous Bollywood veterans of Gujarati heritage include [[Sohrab Modi]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Sohrab Modi (1897–1984)|url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0595271/|website=IMDb|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> [[Asha Parekh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cineplot.com/asha-parekh-memories/ |title=Asha Parekh – Memories |publisher=Cineplot.com |date=28 March 2011 |accessdate=11 September 2011}}</ref> [[Sanjeev Kumar]],<ref>{{cite web|title='Sanjeev Kumar had no ego, Ashok Kumar had a feminine voice'|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/slide-show/slide-show-1-sanjeev-kumar-had-no-ego-ashok-kumar-had-a-feminine-voice/20130725.htm|website=rediff.com|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=People think from my surname Varma that I am Punjabi. But I belong to Kutch so I speak Gujarati and Kutchi. Sanju and I got along well. We spoke in Gujarati on the sets and we ate the same kind of food.}}</ref> [[Jackie Shroff]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Priya Gupta|title=I am reckless: Jackie Shroff|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/I-am-reckless-Jackie-Shroff/articleshow/34292726.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=My father Kakabhai Haribhai Shroff was an astrologer. My father was a Gujarati and my mom Turkish. My mom came from Kazakhstan, where there was a coup and she, along with six sisters and my nani, came down all the way down to Ladakh where they slept on a chatai on ice, down to Delhi and then Mumbai where she met my dad and they got married. My dad was from a wealthy pearl trader's family}}</ref> [[Parveen Babi]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Parveen Babi Biography|url=http://www.iloveindia.com/indian-heroes/parveen-babi.html|website=iloveindia.com|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Parveen Babi was born as Parveen Wali Mohammad Khan Babi to Gujarati Muslim family on April 4, 1949 in the Junagadh district}}</ref>[[Aditya Pancholi]], [[Dimple Kapadia]],<ref name="Film World">{{cite book|title=Film World|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IXlTAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=27 October 2010|year=1973|publisher=T.M. Ramachandran|page=11}}</ref> [[Tina Ambani]], [[Farooq Sheikh]], [[Manmohan Panchamiya]] <ref>{{cite web|title=Vadodara born actor Farooq Sheikh dies of heart attack|url=http://deshgujarat.com/2013/12/28/vadodara-born-actor-farooq-sheikh-dies-of-heart-attack/|website=Desh Gujarat|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> and [[Mehtab (actress)|Mehtab]].<ref name=Cinegems>{{cite web|title=Mehtab-biography|url=http://cinegems.in/mehtab-biography/|website=cinegems.in|publisher=Cinegems.in|accessdate=25 December 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141225135848/http://cinegems.in/mehtab-biography/|archivedate=25 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Mehboob Khan]] was a pioneer of Hindi cinema, best known for directing the social epic drama ''[[Mother India]]'' (1957). As well as film directors such as [[Mehul Kumar]], [[Mahesh Bhatt]] and Shreedatt Vyas<ref>{{cite web|title=Shreedatt Vyas: profile|url=https://www.facebook.com/shreedatt.vyas|website=Facebook|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> Indian theatre personalities include [[Boman Irani]], and [[Alyque Padamsee]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Alyque Padamsee brand of life|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/delhi-times/The-Alyque-Padamsee-brand-of-life/articleshow/27787563.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=23 January 2015|quote=I was born into riches: Ours was a Kutchi business family. My father, Jafferseth, owned 10 buildings and also ran a glassware business. My mother, Kulsumbai Padamsee, ran a furniture business. Anything I wanted was there for the asking. We were eight children in all but I, being born after three daughters, was pampered most. Among Gujarati families, it was only the Padamsees and the royal house of Rajpipla. At school, I learnt to speak in English. Later, our parents learnt the language from us. All that I am today is because of what I learnt at school. Miss Murphy, who ran the school, was an inspirational figure for me.}}</ref> Award-winning producer [[Ismail Merchant]], won six [[Academy Awards]] in collaboration with [[Merchant Ivory Productions]],<ref>{{cite web|title=ISMAIL MERCHANT: IN MEMORY|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/interviews/ismail-merchant-in-memory|website=roger ebert|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> whereas veteran playback singer Jaykar [[Bhojak]] has been performing in the industry for over two decades now.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gujarati music needs to get globalized: Jaykar Bhojak|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/gujarati/music/Jaykar-Bhojak-talks-about-how-Gujarati-music-needs-to-go-global/articleshow/38547708.cms?|website=Times of India|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> Bollywood actresses [[Prachi Desai]] and [[Ameesha Patel]] have found fame in recent times.

[[Manmohan Desai]] is remembered for casting actors like [[Raj Kapoor]], [[Babita Kapoor|Babita]] and [[Amitabh Bachchan]] in hit films he directed such as [[Chhalia]], [[Kismat (1968 film)|Kismat]], and [[Amar Akbar Anthony]], and [[Babubhai Mistry]] pioneered the use of [[special effects]] in films.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.indiaglitz.com/channels/hindi/article/53064.html|title=When yesterday blessed today|publisher=IndiaGlitz}}</ref> Theatre veteran [[Chhel Vayeda]] was well known in [[Hindi cinema]] for being a popular production designer who designed the sets of over 50 films during his lifetime. Meanwhile, film tycoon [[Dalsukh Pancholi]] owned and operated one of the biggest cinema houses in [[Lahore]] and launched the careers of Punjabi film stars such as [[Noor Jehan]] in undivided India.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nevile|first1=Pran|title=Lahore : a sentimental journey|date=2006|publisher=Penguin Books|location=New Delhi, India|isbn=0143061976|page=89|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=0fvNDBqOOToC&pg=PA89&dq=dalsukh+pancholi&hl=en&sa=X&redir_esc=y#v=onepage&q=dalsukh%20pancholi&f=false}}</ref>[[Wadia Movietone]] was a noted Indian film production company and studio based in Mumbai, established in 1933 by Wadia brothers [[J. B. H. Wadia]] and [[Homi Wadia]], whom were originally Parsis from Surat.

Director [[Chaturbhuj Doshi]] is today known as was one of the founding fathers of [[Gujarati cinema]]. [[Gujarati films]] have made artists like [[Naresh Kanodia]], [[Upendra Trivedi]], Snehlata, Raajeev, Roma Maneck, [[Aruna Irani]] and [[Asrani]] popular in the entertainment industry. Among these dynamic actors, the late Upendra Trivedi who was a leading veteran of Gujarati cinema, made a popular pair with the heroine Snehlata and together they co-acted in more than 70 Gujarati films. [[Arvind Trivedi]] by whom the famous character of [[Ravana]] was played in Ramanad Sagar's popular TV serial ''[[Ramayana (TV series)|Ramayana]]'' is his brother. In recent times, Gujarati drama film releases such as ''[[Little Zizou]]'', ''[[Kevi Rite Jaish]]'' and ''[[Premji: Rise of a Warrior]]'' were positively received by audiences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jaiarjun.blogspot.in/2014/10/dry-well-foul-smell-on-ketan-mehtas.html|title=Dry well, foul smell - on Ketan Mehta's excellent ''Bhavni Bhavai''|author=Jai Arjun}}</ref><ref name="nytimes">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/149402/Bhavni-Bhavai/overview|title=Bhavni Bhavai (1980)|publisher=[[New York Times]]|author=Eleanor Mannikka}}</ref><ref name="mm critics">{{cite web|url=http://mayamovies.com/bhavni%20critics.htm |title=Bhavni Bhavai critics/reviews |accessdate=20 December 2014 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141220132640/http://mayamovies.com/bhavni%20critics.htm |archivedate=20 December 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>

Gujarati TV serials which showcase the traditional culture and lifestyle have made a prominent place in India. Comedy actors such as [[Paresh Rawal]], [[Sarita Joshi]], [[Urvashi Dholakia]], [[Ketki Dave]], [[Purbi Joshi]], [[Disha Vakani]], [[Dilip Joshi]], [[Jamnadas Majethia]], [[Deven Bhojani]], [[Rashmi Desai]], [[Satish Shah]], Dina Pathak, Ratna Pathak Shah and [[Supriya Pathak]] have found a place in audience hearts and are presently the top actors on [[Indian television]]. Modern actors of Gujarati heritage who are more versatile include [[Darshan Pandya]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Amrita Mulchandani|title=Looks matter the most in TV: Darshan Pandya|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Looks-matter-the-most-in-TV-Darshan-Pandya/articleshow/17601016.cms|website=the times of india|accessdate=3 April 2015|quote=Looking dapper in the cool denims and hooded jacket, actor Darshan Pandya managed to turn quite a few heads as he struck poses at the River Front during his recent trip to Ahmedabad. The actor, who came into the limelight for his impressive performance in his debut TV show 'Aapki Antara' has been in the news for his recent endeavour in 'Kya Huaa Tera Vaada' where he played Vineet until recently. In town for a personal visit, Darshan says, "I have come here for few days as my parents and sister live here. I watched a film and enjoyed some lovely food in various restaurants in the city."}}</ref> [[Vatsal Seth]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Huma Qureshi tweets for Vatsal Sheth|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/gujarati/Vatsal-Sheth-Huma-Qureshi-supports-Vatsal-Sheth/articleshow/33809052.cms?|website=Times of India|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Gujarati actor Vatsal Sheth is back on the small screen with a bang!}}</ref> [[Avinash Sachdev]], [[Esha Kansara]],<ref>{{cite web|title=TV stars' Navratri musings|url=http://photogallery.indiatimes.com/tv/stars/tv-stars-navratri-musings/articleshow/23639749.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=7 February 2015|quote=ESHA KANSARA: Being a Gujarati, Navratri is a festival that's very close to my heart. I simply love the vibrancy this festival brings with it.}}</ref> [[Shrenu Parikh]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodlife.com/news-gossip/shrenu-parikh-i-travelled-in-trains-without-ticket/|title=Shrenu Parikh: I travelled in trains without ticket!|last=IANS|access-date=2018-06-29|language=en-US}}</ref> [[Amar Upadhyay]], [[Viraf Patel]], [[Ajaz Khan]], [[Sameer Dattani]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=Baker|first1=Steven|title="My work has gone to another level" – Sammir Dattani|url=http://bollyspice.com/3137/my-work-has-gone-to-another-level-sammir-dattani|website=Bollyspice.com|accessdate=23 January 2015|quote=Your family is Gujarati, you were born and brought up in Bombay, and you have worked in Hindi, Kannada and Tamil cinema, so what languages do you speak? Well I speak Kannada. I speak Gujarati, Hindi of course, English of course, and a bit of Marathi and Telugu.}}</ref> 
[[Karishma Tanna]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Upen Patel proposes Karishma Tanna inside Bigg Boss, her craze is rising outside!|url=http://buddybits.com/upen-patel-proposes-karishma-tanna-inside-bigg-boss-craze-rising-outside/|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> [[Drashti Dhami]],<ref>{{cite web|last1=|author1=Amrita Mulchandani|title=Link-up rumours don't really bother me: Drashti Dhami|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Link-up-rumours-dont-really-bother-me-Drashti-Dhami/articleshow/13848151.cms|website=The Times of India|accessdate=24 January 2015|quote=Chirpy, Dhrasti Dhami exudes great energy not just on the small screen, but insists she is the same in real life too. Dhrasti has a strong Gujarat connect and is proud of her roots. "I am a very proud Gujarati. I have lots of relatives in Surat, but it's been quite some time since I have been there. I came to Ahmedabad as a child, but haven't visited the city for some time," she says.}}</ref> Disha Savla,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ano Patel|title=Gujaratis take the lead on prime time TV|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Gujaratis-take-the-lead-on-prime-time-TV/articleshow/44754981.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Hometown: Kutch. As the nagging wife Bobby in Neeli Chhatri Wale, Disha Savla has made quite an impression, and shares screen space with Yashpal Sharma. The actress who hails from Kutch has been part of a number of plays in Mumbai and has also done a Gujarati show on TV. Making her debut on Hindi TV, she says, "The Gujarati show has prepared me for taking this next step. It is a very different concept so I hope this show clicks with the audience."}}</ref> 
Komal Thacker,<ref>{{cite web|title=Komal Thacker: profile|url=https://www.facebook.com/komal.thacker.754?fref=pb&hc_location=friends_tab&pnref=friends.all|website=Facebook|accessdate=3 April 2015}}</ref> Vasim Bloch,<ref>{{cite web|title=Vasim Bloch: profile|url=https://www.facebook.com/vasim.bloch.50?fref=pb&hc_location=friends_tab&pnref=friends.all|website=Facebook|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> Parth Oza,<ref>{{cite web|title=Parth Oza: Artography|url=http://parthoza.com/#Dr-Parth-Oza|website=parthoza.com|accessdate=7 February 2015}}</ref> [[Tanvi Vyas]], [[Nisha Rawal]], [[Karan Suchak]],<ref>{{cite web|author1=Ano Patel|title=Gujaratis take the lead on prime time TV|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/news/hindi/Gujaratis-take-the-lead-on-prime-time-TV/articleshow/44754981.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Karan Suchak Hometown: Ahmedabad. After playing character roles in Ek Hazaaron Mein Meri Behna Hai, Savitri and Pavitra Rishta, Karan shot to fame as Dhrishtadyumna in Mahabharat. Now playing Raja Vikramaditya in Singhasan Battisi, Karan says, "I was born in Ahmedabad and I am a Gujarati. It's only been a few months for me in this industry and it has been a busy journey, I hope it remains that way."}}</ref> Jugal Jethi,<ref>{{cite web|title=Jugal Jethi|url=https://www.facebook.com/jugal.jethi?fref=ts|website=Facebook|accessdate=8 March 2015}}</ref> [[Isha Sharvani]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Isha Sharvani: I call myself a global Gujarati|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Isha-Sharvani-I-call-myself-a-global-Gujarati/articleshow/45992064.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=7 February 2015|quote=Actress-danseuse Isha Sharvani who was in Vadodara to perform at a mega art and culture festival, says, "My mother is a Gujarati and I have very fond memories of Gujarat.}}</ref> Pia Trivedi,<ref>{{cite news|title=New kid on the block: Pia Trivedi|url=http://staging.stargold.in/newsdetails.aspx?nid=2197|publisher=stargold.in|accessdate=24 January 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150206222832/http://staging.stargold.in/newsdetails.aspx?nid=2197|archivedate=6 February 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Sanjeeda Sheikh]]<ref>{{cite web|author1=Anil Mulchandani|title=Shining stars|url=http://indiatoday.intoday.in/story/shining-stars/0/130139.html|website=india today|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> [[Pooja Gor]], [[Payal Rohatgi]], [[Ravish Desai]], [[Shefali Zariwala]], and [[Shenaz Treasurywala]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Shenaz Treasurywala|url=http://www.kaneesha.com/shenaz-treasurywala|website=kaneesha.com|accessdate=6 February 2015|quote=Shenaz Treasurywala is a famed Indian model, actress, VJ and a Travel writer. Born on 29th June, 1981 in Mumbai, Shenaz Treasurywala belongs to a middle class Gujarati speaking Parsi family.}}</ref>

There are dedicated [[List of Gujarati language television channels|television channels]] airing Gujarati programs.

Well known musicians include the internationally acclaimed [[Kalyanji-Anandji]], [[Vasant Rai]], pop star [[Alisha Chinai]], Darshan Raval,<ref>{{cite web|author1=Abhimanyu Mishra|title=Darshan Rawal enters the final four on reality show|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/tv/trade-news/gujarati/Darshan-Rawal-Darshan-Rawal-enters-the-final-four/articleshow/45174686.cms?|website=The Times of India|accessdate=16 April 2015|quote=Darshan Rawal has been quite a sensation with his signature style singing and an adorable personality which has won him many fans.}}</ref> [[Vishal–Shekhar|Shekhar Ravjiani]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Not thought of acting as of now: Shekhar|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/music/news/Not-thought-of-acting-as-of-now-Shekhar/articleshow/17767758.cms|website=Times of India|accessdate=8 February 2015|quote=I belong to Jamnagar but my mother has many friends in Ahmedabad. I miss eating ice-candies and listening to Gujarati folk music during Navratri. I want to travel to the interiors of Gujarat and some places in Kutch, and interact with the local musicians who compose on those rare musical instruments. What attracts me is the strong folk music heritage that Gujarat has kept alive after so many years.}}</ref> [[Salim–Sulaiman]], sons of Sadruddin Merchant who is veteran composer of the film industry, and ghazal singer [[Pankaj Udhas]] who is recipient of the [[Padma Shri]]. Famous sports icons of Gujarati heritage include [[Karsan Ghavri]], [[Deepak Shodhan]], [[Ashok Mankad]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Cricketers have become too aggressive: Gavaskar|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/vadodara/Cricketers-have-become-too-aggressive-Gavaskar/articleshow/49426650.cms|website=the times of India|accessdate=19 November 2015|quote=Sunil Gavaskar had the audience in splits when he said how he learnt Gujarati. "We had two Gujaratis, Ashok Mankad and Karsan Ghavri, in Mumbai team and others were Maharashtrians. Mankad and Ghavri